# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: african-american-culture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] Notable buildings along 125th Street include the Apollo Theater, the Adam Clayton Powell Jr.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] State Office Building, the Hotel Theresa, the Studio Museum in Harlem, the Mount Morris Bank Building, Harlem Commonwealth Council, the Harlem Children's Zone, the Church of St.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] Joseph of the Holy Family, and the former West End Theatre, now home to the La Gree Baptist Church.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] The street was designated by the Commissioners' Plan of 1811 that established the Manhattan street grid as one of 15 east–west streets that would be 100 feet (30 m) in width (while other streets were designated as 60 feet (18 m) in width).
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] The western part of the street runs diagonally between the neighborhoods of Manhattanville and Morningside Heights from the northwest from the West Harlem Piers and an interchange with the Henry Hudson Parkway at 130th Street.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] East of Morningside Avenue it runs east–west through central Harlem to Second Avenue, where a ramp connects it to the Robert F.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] However, 125th Street continues to First Avenue, where it connects to the southbound FDR Drive and the Willis Avenue Bridge.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] West of Convent Avenue, 125th Street was rerouted onto what was, prior to 1920, called Manhattan Street.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] What remains of the original alignment of 125th Street was renamed La Salle Street at that time.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] The remaining blocks run between Amsterdam Avenue and Claremont Avenue.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] *The New York Times* lamented the name changes, noting that the new names had "somewhat doubtful nomenclature", and that the City's "Aldermen like French names" but gave no rationale for the moves otherwise.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] A block of the original 125th Street in this area was de-mapped to make the super-blocks where the Grant Houses projects now exist.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] A proposal to convert the street into a Trans-Harlem Expressway died when funds were diverted from the proposed 125th Street Hudson River bridge at the street's western end.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] Beginning in the late 1990s, many sections of 125th Street have been gentrified and developed with such stores as MAC Cosmetics, Old Navy, H&M, CVS/pharmacy, and Magic Johnson Theaters.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] In collaboration with the community, the city has developed a plan for the 125th Street corridor focusing on reinforcing and building upon its strengths as an arts and cultural corridor.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] A rift in the crust runs along underneath this street from the East River to New Jersey and is known as the **125th Street Fault** or the **Manhattanville Fault**.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] It is suspected to have caused a magnitude-5.2 earthquake in 1737, two smaller ones in 1981, and a 2.4 magnitude quake in 2001.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] The fault line skims across the top of Central Park and runs to Roosevelt Island to the southeast.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] It creates a fault valley deep enough to require the IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line (1 train) to use a trestle between 122nd and 135th Streets, even though the line goes underground at either end and remains at the same elevation above sea level throughout.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] Riverside Drive also crosses over the fault valley on a high viaduct.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] Metro-North Railroad's Harlem–125th Street station is located at the street's intersection with Park Avenue.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] The planned second phase of the Second Avenue Subway, continuing north from the 116th Street station, will turn westward onto 125th Street, terminating at a station at Lexington Avenue.
[src:african-american-culture/125th-street-manhattan] The new station would connect to the Metro-North and preexisting Lexington Avenue subway stations there.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 2, 2004.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent Republican president George W.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush and his running mate, incumbent vice president Dick Cheney, were elected to a second term.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They narrowly defeated the Democratic ticket of Massachusetts junior senator John Kerry and North Carolina senior senator John Edwards.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush and Cheney were re-nominated by their party with no difficulty.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Meanwhile, the Democrats engaged in a competitive primary.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry emerged as the early front-runner but was faced with serious opposition by former Vermont governor Howard Dean, who briefly surged ahead of Kerry in the polls.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry won the first set of primaries in January and re-emerged as the front-runner, and Dean dropped out in February.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry clinched his party's nomination in March after a series of primary victories over runner-up Edwards, whom he ultimately selected to be his running mate.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The September 11 attacks in 2001 decisively reshaped Bush's foreign policy goals and garnered him near-universal support early in his term.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, by 2004 his management of the war on terror attracted serious debate, particularly over his handling of the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush presented himself as a decisive leader and attacked Kerry as a "flip-flopper"; Kerry had voted to authorize the invasion, but criticized Bush's conduct of the Iraq War.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Domestic issues were debated as well, including the economy and jobs, health care, abortion, same-sex marriage, and embryonic stem cell research.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush won by a narrow margin of 35 electoral votes and took 50.7% of the popular vote.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush swept the South and the Mountain states and took the crucial swing states of Ohio, Iowa, and New Mexico, the last two flipping Republican.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although Kerry flipped New Hampshire, Bush won both more electoral votes and states than in 2000.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ohio was the tipping-point state, and was considered to be the state that allowed Bush to win reelection.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some aspects of the election process were subject to controversy, although not to the degree seen in the 2000 presidential election.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush won Florida by a 5% margin, a significant improvement over his razor-thin victory margin in the state four years earlier that had led to a legal challenge in *Bush v.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This remains the most recent presidential election in which the Republican candidate won Colorado, New Mexico, and Virginia.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the time, Bush received the most popular votes in history, a record that would be broken in 2008.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush's win was the only Republican popular vote victory during the eight elections from 1992 to 2020.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush is the only incumbent Republican president to have won a second term since Ronald Reagan in 1984, and the only Republican presidential candidate to have won a majority of the popular vote since his father in 1988.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush won the presidency in 2000 after the U.S.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gore* remanded the case to the Florida Supreme Court, which declared there was not sufficient time to hold a recount without violating the U.S.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Just eight months into Bush's presidency, the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, suddenly transformed him into a wartime president.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His approval ratings surged to near 90%.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Within a month, the forces of a coalition led by the United States entered Afghanistan, which had been sheltering Osama bin Laden, suspected mastermind of the September 11 attacks.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Taliban had been removed by December, although a long reconstruction would follow.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Bush administration then turned its attention to Iraq and argued the need to remove Saddam Hussein from power in Iraq had become urgent.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Among the stated reasons were that Saddam's regime had tried to acquire nuclear material and had not properly accounted for biological and chemical material it was known to have previously possessed.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Both the possession of these weapons of mass destruction (WMD), and the failure to account for them, would violate the UN sanctions.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The assertion about WMD was hotly advanced by the Bush administration from the beginning, but other major powers including China, France, Germany, and Russia remained unconvinced that Iraq was a threat and refused to allow passage of a UN Security Council resolution to authorize the use of force.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Iraq permitted UN weapon inspectors in November 2002, who were continuing their work to assess the WMD claim when the Bush administration decided to proceed with war without UN authorization and told the inspectors to leave the country.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The United States invaded Iraq on March 20, 2003, along with a "coalition of the willing" that consisted of additional troops from the United Kingdom, and to a lesser extent, from Australia and Poland.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Within about three weeks, the invasion caused the collapse of both the Iraqi government and its armed forces; however, the U.S. and allied forces failed to find any weapon of mass destruction in Iraq.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nevertheless, on May 1, Bush landed on the aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln*, in a Lockheed S-3 Viking, where he gave a speech announcing the end of "major combat operations" in the Iraq War.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Both candidates were not only graduates of Yale University, but both were also members of the exclusive Skull and Bones society.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It is the only time two "Bonesmen" have faced each other for the presidency.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush was able to ward off any serious challenge to the Republican nomination.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator Lincoln Chafee from Rhode Island considered challenging Bush on an anti-war platform in New Hampshire but decided not to run after the capture of Saddam Hussein in December 2003.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On March 10, 2004, Bush officially attained the number of delegates needed to be nominated at the 2004 Republican National Convention in New York City.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He accepted the nomination on September 2, 2004, and retained Vice President Dick Cheney as his running mate.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the convention and throughout the campaign, Bush focused on two themes: defending America against terrorism and building an ownership society.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The ownership society included allowing people to invest some of their Social Security in the stock market, increasing home and stock ownership, and encouraging more people to buy their own health insurance.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 2004 Democratic Party presidential primaries took place from January 14 to June 8, 2004, to select the Democratic Party's nominee for president.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Before the primaries, Vermont governor Howard Dean was a favorite to win the nomination; however, Massachusetts senator John Kerry won victories in two early races: the Iowa caucuses and the New Hampshire primary.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These wins strengthened Kerry's previously weak campaign.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] By March 11, Kerry had received enough delegates to win the nomination.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Other major candidates included North Carolina senator John Edwards and retired U.S.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry asked Republican senator John McCain to be his running mate but McCain turned down his offer.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On July 6, Kerry selected Edwards as his running mate, shortly before the 2004 Democratic National Convention was held later that month in Boston.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Heading into the convention, the Kerry–Edwards ticket unveiled its new slogan: a promise to make America "stronger at home and more respected in the world".
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry made his Vietnam War experience the convention's prominent theme.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The keynote address at the convention was delivered by Illinois state senator and U.S.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senate candidate and future president Barack Obama; the speech was well received, and it elevated Obama's status within the Democratic Party.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There were four other presidential tickets on the ballot in a number of states totaling enough electoral votes to have a theoretical possibility of winning a majority in the Electoral College.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ahead of the 2004 election, some states implemented electronic voting systems.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Critics raised several issues about voting machines, particularly those made by Diebold Election Systems.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Cybersecurity professionals found security vulnerabilities in Diebold machines.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Voting machines made by several companies were also criticized for their lack of a paper trail, which would have made results easier to verify.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Democrats also criticized various executives at Diebold, Inc.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] (the parent company of Diebold Election Systems) for their support of Bush's campaign, stating that it constituted a conflict of interest.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Following these issues, California banned the use of Diebold's AccuVote TSX voting machines for elections in 2004.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 2004 election was the first to be affected by the campaign finance reforms mandated by the Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act of 2002.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The act created restrictions on fundraising by political parties and candidates.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A large number of independent 527 groups were created to bypass these restrictions.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Named for a section of the Internal Revenue Code, these groups were able to raise large amounts of money for various political causes as long as they did not coordinate their activities with political campaigns.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Examples of 527s include Swift Boat Veterans for Truth, MoveOn.org, the Media Fund, and America Coming Together.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These groups were active throughout the campaign season, spending a record $556 million for all elections in 2004.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Stand by Your Ad provision of the Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act required political advertisements on television to include a verbal disclaimer identifying the organization or campaign responsible for the advertisement.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This provision was intended to force campaigns to take responsibility for negative advertisements.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Campaign strategists criticized this requirement, stating that it would waste time and cause voters to be confused.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry's campaign managers believed that Kerry had an advantage on domestic issues.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush's campaign also focused on increasing voter turnout among conservatives.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] According to one exit poll, people who voted for Bush cited the issues of terrorism and traditional values as the most important factors in their decision.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry supporters cited the war in Iraq, the economy and jobs, and health care.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Tax cuts were passed in 2001 and 2003 under the Bush administration with Bush's support.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the 2004 campaign, Bush praised these tax cuts, stating that they helped to grow the economy.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the other hand, Kerry attacked Bush for failing to create jobs under his presidency.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry stated that he wanted to reduce the United States budget deficit by capping government spending while ending various tax breaks for businesses.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry also supported tax credits for businesses that hire additional workers.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush attacked Kerry for his economic proposals, stating that they would cause Americans to pay higher taxes.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush also attacked Kerry for previously supporting tax raises, such as a proposed increase on the federal gas tax.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush defended the Iraq War, arguing that it was necessary to stop terrorism.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also said that the United States had made progress stopping terrorism in other nations.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush attacked Kerry for opposing the Iraq War after voting to authorize it in 2002, characterizing the shift as one of many flip-flops by Kerry.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry argued that Bush had misled the American public in pursuing the Iraq War, noting that no illegal weapons had been found in Iraq.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He said that the Iraq War was a mistake and a diversion from terrorism in other nations such as Afghanistan.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the election, exit polls found that foreign policy concerns were the most important issues for voters.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Health savings accounts (HSAs) were introduced in 2004 as part of the Medicare Prescription Drug, Improvement, and Modernization Act, signed by Bush in December 2003.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As part of his 2004 campaign, Bush supported the expansion of HSAs.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He proposed tax cuts to help Americans purchase their own health insurance.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also proposed a plan that would allow small businesses to purchase health insurance in large groups.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry's health care proposals included government subsidies for businesses that provide health insurance and the expansion of government-run health care programs.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Health policy experts stated that Bush's proposals would have a more limited impact than Kerry's proposals.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry also attacked Bush for his policy on stem cell research.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In 2001, the Bush administration restricted embryonic stem cell research to existing stem cell lines.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry stated that this restriction was a barrier to conducting important research.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In July 2004, Bush announced his support for a Constitutional amendment to ban same-sex marriage, shortly before the Senate voted on the amendment.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although Kerry stated that he opposed same-sex marriage, he also opposed the amendment, saying that the legality of same-sex marriage should be decided by individual states.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the campaign, Bush was accused of failing to fulfill his required service in the Texas Air National Guard.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A scandal occurred at CBS News after they aired a segment on *60 Minutes Wednesday*, introducing what became known as the Killian documents.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These documents were allegedly written by Jerry B.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Killian, Bush's squadron commander, and they contained various allegations about Bush's service.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Serious doubts about the documents' authenticity quickly emerged, leading CBS to appoint a review panel that eventually resulted in the firing of the news producer and other significant staffing changes.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Killian documents were eventually concluded to be forgeries.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry was accused by the Swift Vets and POWs for Truth of distorting his military service in Vietnam.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The group challenged the legitimacy of each of the combat medals awarded to Kerry by the U.S.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Navy, and the disposition of his discharge.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The organization spent $22.4 million in advertisements against Kerry.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the election, political analysts described their advertising campaign as effective.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The term swiftboating was used during the campaign to describe the organization's negative advertising, which Democrats saw as unfair.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was also used after the campaign to generally describe a harsh attack by a political opponent that is dishonest, personal and unfair.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Three presidential debates and one vice presidential debate were organized by the Commission on Presidential Debates, and held in the autumn of 2004.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On October 29, four days before the election, excerpts of a video of Osama bin Laden addressing the American people were broadcast on al Jazeera.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In his remarks, bin Laden mentions the September 11 attacks, and taunted Bush over his response to them.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the days following the video's release, Bush's lead over Kerry increased by several points.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Elections analysts and political pundits issue probabilistic forecasts of the composition of the Electoral College.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These forecasts use a variety of factors to estimate the likelihood of each candidate winning the Electoral College electors for that state.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Below is a list of states considered by one or more forecasts to be competitive; states that are not deemed to be "safe" or "solid" by at least one of the forecasters *The Cook Political Report*, *The New York Times*, and CNN.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] (a) *One faithless elector from Minnesota cast an electoral vote for John Edwards (written as John Ewards) for president.* (b) *In Montana, Karen Sanchirico was listed on the ballot as Nader's running mate, not Camejo.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In New York, Nader appeared on two distinct tickets, one with Camejo and one with Pierce.* (c) *Because Arrin Hawkins, then aged 28, was constitutionally ineligible to serve as vice president, Margaret Trowe replaced her on the ballot in some states.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the 3,154 counties/districts/independent cities making returns, Bush won the popular vote in 2,568 (81.42%) while Kerry carried 586 (18.58%).
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The following table records the official vote tallies for each state as reported by the official Federal Election Commission report.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The column labeled "Margin" shows Bush's margin of victory over Kerry (the margin is negative for states and districts won by Kerry).
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although Guam has no votes in the Electoral College, it has held a straw poll for its presidential preference since 1980.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Maine and Nebraska each allowed for their electoral votes to be split between candidates.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In both states, two electoral votes were awarded to the winner of the statewide race and one electoral vote was awarded to the winner of each congressional district.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Red font color denotes those won by Republican President George W.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush; blue denotes states won by Democrat John Kerry.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] One elector in Minnesota cast a ballot for president with the name of "John Ewards" [*sic*] written on it.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Electoral College officials certified this ballot as a vote for Edwards for president.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The remaining nine electors cast ballots for Kerry.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] All ten electors in the state cast ballots for Edwards for vice president (Edwards's name was spelled correctly on all ballots for vice president).
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the first time in U.S. history that an elector had cast a vote for the same person to be both president and vice president.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Electoral balloting in Minnesota was performed by secret ballot, and none of the electors admitted to casting the Edwards vote for president, so it may never be known who the faithless elector was.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It is not even known whether the vote for Edwards was deliberate or unintentional; the Republican Secretary of State and several of the Democratic electors have expressed the opinion that this was an accident.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the campaign and as the results came in on the night of the election, there was much focus on Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Florida.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These three swing states were seen as evenly divided, and with each casting 20 electoral votes or more, they had the power to decide the election.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the final results came in, Kerry took Pennsylvania and then Bush took Florida, focusing all attention on Ohio.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The morning after the election, the winner was still undetermined.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The result in Ohio would decide the winner, although the results in New Mexico and Iowa were also undetermined.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush led in Ohio, but the state was still counting provisional ballots.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the afternoon of the day after the election, Ohio Secretary of State Ken Blackwell announced that there were roughly 135,000 provisional ballots remaining.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry's campaign believed that it was statistically impossible to erase Bush's lead.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Faced with this announcement, Kerry conceded defeat.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush became the first Republican to ever win without carrying New Hampshire, and the first to win the popular vote without Vermont and Illinois.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the last time a president was re-elected to a consecutive term with a higher share of the electoral or popular vote.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush carried Colorado despite the state being Kerry's birth state.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush simultaneously lost his own birth state of Connecticut, making this the only election since 1864 where neither candidate carried their birth state.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This election was the first time since 1976 that New Jersey, Connecticut, Vermont, Maine, Illinois, Michigan, and California voted for the losing candidate in the popular vote, the first time since 1980 that Maryland did so, and the first time since 1948 that Delaware did so.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush's 2.4% popular vote margin is the smallest ever for a re-elected incumbent president, surpassing the 1812 election.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush won three states that have not voted Republican since: Virginia, Colorado, and New Mexico.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Virginia had voted Republican in every election from 1968 to 2004 but conversely has voted Democratic in every election since 2008.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In contrast, this is the last election in which the losing candidate won any of the following states: Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This is also the last time a Republican was elected without carrying Maine's 2nd congressional district.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This election is the only time in history that every Northeastern state voted Democratic and every former Confederate state voted Republican in the same election.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Thus, Bush is the only candidate to win without carrying any Northeastern electoral votes.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Furthermore, this was the last election where both major party tickets consisted entirely of white men.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This is also the most recent election that the incumbent party would flip any states, with Bush becoming the first Republican since 1984 to win the state of Iowa, and since 1988 to win the state of New Mexico, both states he did not win in 2000.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the last election where Nevada voted Republican until 2024; and Florida, Iowa, and Ohio until 2016.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This is the only presidential election since 1988 in which a Republican nominee won the national popular vote with a majority, and it remains the only presidential election since 1984 in which an incumbent Republican president won a second consecutive term.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush became the only incumbent president to win consecutive re-election after previously losing the popular vote.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush was also the first of only two presidents to win the Electoral College while losing the popular vote in a previous election but later winning both the Electoral College and the popular vote in a subsequent election.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush is the seventh Republican to have won re-election to a consecutive term, along with Abraham Lincoln, Ulysses S.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Eisenhower, Richard Nixon, and Ronald Reagan.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush was also the last Republican to win a second term in the White House until Donald Trump in 2024.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 2004 election had the highest turnout rate among eligible voters since 1968.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the first presidential election since 1988 where a candidate won a majority of the popular vote.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the last time a Republican nominee won the national popular vote until Donald Trump in 2024.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This remains the most recent presidential election in which both major party candidates flipped at least one state.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In addition, this was one of only two elections in the 21st century in which a candidate from either party won fewer than 20 states, with the other being 2024, when Kamala Harris won 19 states, the same as John Kerry.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This is the most recent instance in which both major party tickets did not include a woman or a person of color.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This, along with the previous election would be the only ones between 1980 and 2024 where the winner won fewer than 300 electoral votes (or below 55% of the electoral college vote).
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This is also the last winning ticket that did not have Joe Biden or Donald Trump on it.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In 2004, voters with and without college degrees were roughly evenly split along partisan lines.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] By 2024, voters with college degrees were Democratic-leaning, while voters without college degrees were Republican-leaning.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] After the election, activists and election scholars criticized various issues with the election in Ohio.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Long lines at polling places over seven hours were reported.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] An electronic voting machine erroneously gave thousands of extra votes to Bush.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Foley stated that he believed that Ohio's voting problems did not affect the outcome.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] After the election, many blogs published false rumors claiming to show evidence that voter fraud had prevented Kerry from winning.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Although the overall result of the election was not challenged by the Kerry campaign, Green Party presidential candidate David Cobb and Libertarian Party presidential candidate Michael Badnarik obtained a recount in Ohio.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This recount was completed December 28, 2004, although on January 24, 2007, a jury convicted two Ohio elections officials of selecting precincts to recount where they already knew the hand total would match the machine total, thereby avoiding having to perform a full recount.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Independent candidate Ralph Nader obtained a recount in 11 New Hampshire precincts that used Accuvote voting machines.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] At the official counting of the electoral votes on January 6, an objection was made under the Electoral Count Act (now 3 U.S.C. § 15) to Ohio's electoral votes.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Because the motion was supported by at least one member of both the House of Representatives and the Senate, the law required that the two houses separate to debate and vote on the objection.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the House of Representatives, the objection was supported by 31 Democrats.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was opposed by 178 Republicans, 88 Democrats and one independent.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Not voting were 52 Republicans and 80 Democrats.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Four people elected to the House had not yet taken office, and one seat was vacant.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the Senate, it was supported only by its maker, Barbara Boxer, with 74 senators opposed and 25 not voting.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] During the debate, no Senator argued that the outcome of the election should be changed by either court challenge or revote.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Boxer claimed that she had made the motion not to challenge the outcome but "to cast the light of truth on a flawed system which must be fixed now".
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Kerry would later state that "the widespread irregularities make it impossible to know for certain that the [Ohio] outcome reflected the will of the voters".
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the same article, Democratic National Committee Chairman Howard Dean said: "I'm not confident that the election in Ohio was fairly decided...
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] We know that there was substantial voter suppression, and the machines were not reliable.
[src:african-american-culture/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It should not be a surprise that the Republicans are willing to do things that are unethical to manipulate elections.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph was born and raised in Florida.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] He was educated at Cookman Institute, then moved to New York City as part of the early Great Migration, leaving behind the discriminatory Jim Crow–era south.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] There he became convinced that overcoming racism required collective action and he was drawn to socialism and workers' rights.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] He unsuccessfully ran for state office on the socialist ticket in the early 1920s, but found more success in organizing for African American workers' rights.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1963, Randolph was the head of the March on Washington, organized by Bayard Rustin, at which Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his "I Have a Dream" speech.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph inspired the "Freedom Budget", sometimes called the "Randolph Freedom budget", which aimed to deal with the economic problems facing the Black community.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] It was published by the Randolph Institute in January 1967 as "A Freedom Budget for All Americans".
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Asa Philip Randolph was born April 15, 1889, in Crescent City, Florida, the second son of James William Randolph, a tailor and minister in an African Methodist Episcopal Church, and Elizabeth Robinson Randolph, a seamstress.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1891, the family moved to Jacksonville, Florida, which had a thriving, well-established African-American community.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's father taught him that color was less important than a person's character and conduct.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] His mother taught him the importance of education and of defending oneself physically against those who tried to hurt one or one's family, if necessary.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph remembered vividly the night his mother sat in the front room of their house with a loaded shotgun across her lap, while his father tucked a pistol under his coat and went off to prevent a mob from lynching a man at the local county jail.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Asa and his brother, James, were superior students.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] They attended the Cookman Institute in East Jacksonville, the only academic high school in Florida for African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Asa excelled in literature, drama, and public speaking; he also starred on the school's baseball team, sang solos with the school choir, and was valedictorian of the 1907 graduating class.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] After graduation, Randolph worked odd jobs and devoted his time to singing, acting, and reading.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Du Bois's *The Souls of Black Folk* convinced him that the fight for social equality was most important.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Barred by discrimination from all but manual jobs in the South, Randolph moved to New York City in 1911, where he worked odd jobs and took social sciences courses at City College.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1913, Randolph courted and married Lucille Campbell Green, a widow, Howard University graduate, and entrepreneur who shared his socialist politics.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] She earned enough money to support them both.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Shortly after Randolph's marriage, he helped organize the Shakespearean Society in Harlem.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] With them he played the roles of Hamlet, Othello, and Romeo, among others.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph aimed to become an actor but gave up after failing to win his parents' approval.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's background as a Shakespearean actor gave him a "deep, resonant voice" that he used to considerable effect in his speeches while his dignified, "courtly" bearing assisted with negotiations.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In New York, Randolph became familiar with socialism and the ideologies espoused by the Industrial Workers of the World.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] He met Columbia University law student Chandler Owen, and the two developed a synthesis of Marxist economics and the sociological ideas of Lester Frank Ward, arguing that people could be free only if not subject to economic deprivation.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] At this point, Randolph developed what became his distinctive form of civil rights activism, which emphasized the importance of collective action as a way for Black people to gain legal and economic equality.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] To this end, he and Owen opened an employment office in Harlem to provide job training for southern migrants and encourage them to join trade unions.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Like others in the labor movement, Randolph favored immigration restriction.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] He opposed African Americans' having to compete with people willing to work for low wages.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] But unlike other immigration restrictionists, he rejected the notions of racial hierarchy that became popular in the 1920s.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1917, Randolph and Owen founded *The Messenger* with the help of the Socialist Party of America.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] It was a radical monthly magazine that campaigned against lynching, opposed U.S. participation in World War I, and urged African Americans to resist being drafted, fight for an integrated society, and join radical unions.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Soon thereafter, the editorial staff of *The Messenger* became divided by three issues: the growing rift between West Indian and African Americans, support for the Bolshevik revolution, and support for Marcus Garvey's Back-to-Africa movement.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1919, most West Indian radicals joined the new Communist Party, while African-American leftists—Randolph included—mostly supported the Socialist Party.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] The infighting left *The Messenger* short of financial support, and it went into decline.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph unsuccessfully ran on the Socialist Party ticket for New York State Comptroller in 1920 and for Secretary of State of New York in 1922.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's first experience with labor organization came in 1917, when he organized a union of elevator operators in New York City.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1919 he became president of the National Brotherhood of Workers of America, a union that organized among African-American shipyard and dock workers in the Tidewater region of Virginia.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] The union dissolved in 1921 under pressure from the American Federation of Labor.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's greatest success came with the Brotherhood of Sleeping Car Porters (BSCP), which elected him president in 1925.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] This was the first serious effort to form a labor institution for employees of the Pullman Company, a major employer of African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] The railroads had dramatically expanded in the early 20th century, and the jobs offered relatively good employment at a time of widespread racial discrimination.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] But because porters were not unionized, most had poor working conditions and were underpaid.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Under Randolph's direction, the BSCP enrolled 51 percent of porters within a year, to which Pullman responded with violence and firings.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1928, after failing to win mediation under the Watson-Parker Railway Labor Act, Randolph planned a strike.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] This was postponed after rumors circulated that Pullman had 5,000 replacement workers ready to take the place of BSCP members.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] As a result of its perceived ineffectiveness, membership in the union declined; by 1933 it had only 658 members and electricity and telephone service at headquarters had been disconnected because of nonpayment of bills.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] The American historian William Harris wrote: "Randolph functioned mainly as a symbolic figure and spokesman.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] He was in the tradition of those Black leaders—they can be seen in the church and Black advancement organizations, as well as in politics—whose influence has derived largely from rhetoric and personal presence.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] But despite his superb rhetorical abilities and presence, Randolph was indecisive and prone to compromise".
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Harris described Randolph as the most charismatic Afro-American leader of his generation, writing: "Handsome, almost exquisite in bearing, and a master of the arts of oratory and rhetoric, his speech had a hypnotic effect upon his audience.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] The BSCP's fortunes changed with the 1932 election of President Franklin D.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] With amendments to the Railway Labor Act in 1934, porters were granted rights under federal law.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Membership in the Brotherhood jumped to more than 7,000.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] After years of bitter struggle, the Pullman Company began to negotiate with the Brotherhood in 1935, and agreed to a contract with it in 1937.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Employees gained $2,000,000 in pay increases, a shorter workweek, and overtime pay.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph maintained the Brotherhood's affiliation with the American Federation of Labor through the 1955 AFL-CIO merger.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Through his success with the BSCP, Randolph emerged as one of the most visible spokespeople for African-American civil rights.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] He called shaping public opinion "the most powerful weapon in America" and by 1940 had become the face of the U.S. civil rights movement.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In September 1940, at the annual BSCP convention in Harlem, Randolph urged the Roosevelt administration to have no discrimination in the Selective Training and Service Act, which was being debated in Congress at the time.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was a speaker at the convention, and through her, Randolph obtained a meeting at the White House with President Franklin D.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] At the meeting, Roosevelt promised Randolph there would be no segregation in the military, saying he was sympathetic to the civil rights movement.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Two weeks later, the War Department issued a statement saying "the policy of the War Department is not to intermingle colored and white enlisted personnel".
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Feeling betrayed, Randolph launched nationwide protests demanding the end of segregation in not only the military but also the industries that made weapons for it.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] At the time, the Roosevelt administration was gearing up to make the U.S.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] "the arsenal of democracy" by supplying a massive number of weapons to the United Kingdom and its allies that were fighting in World War II, and banning segregation in the defense-related industry would be a huge gain for the civil rights movement.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph told an aide: "I think we ought to have 10,000 Negros march down Pennsylvania Avenue...We shall not call upon our white friends to march with us.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] There are some things that Negros must do on their own".
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1941, Randolph, Bayard Rustin, and A.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Muste proposed a march on Washington to protest racial discrimination in war industries, an end to segregation, access to defense employment, the proposal of an anti-lynching law, and the desegregation of the U.S. armed forces.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's belief in the power of peaceful direct action was inspired partly by Mahatma Gandhi's success using such tactics during the Indian independence movement.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph threatened to have 50,000 Black people march on Washington.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In early May 1941, Randolph made the call for a march on Washington, which generated immense enthusiasm among Afro-Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] On 18 June 1941, Randolph again met with Roosevelt at the White House with the mayor of New York, Fiorello La Guardia, serving as a mediator.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Roosevelt asked Randolph to call off the march, saying "questions like this cannot be settled with a sledgehammer", and vaguely promised to have discussions if the march was canceled.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph said the march would not be canceled unless Roosevelt gave way.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] La Guardia broke the impasse by saying: "Gentlemen, it is clear that Mr.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph is not going to call off the march, and I suggest we all begin to seek a formula".
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] The march was canceled after Roosevelt issued Executive Order 8802, or the Fair Employment Act.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Some activists, including Rustin, felt betrayed because Roosevelt's order banned discrimination only in war industries, not the armed forces.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Nonetheless, the Fair Employment Act is generally considered an important early civil rights victory.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Executive Order 8802 read: "There shall be no discrimination in the employment of workers in defense industries or the government because of race, creed, color or national origin".
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph dropped his demand for an integrated military, which he seems to have privately regarded as unrealistic and only made as a bargaining chip in his talks with Roosevelt.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] The draft involved young men from all 48 states, and the bloc of conservative Southern whites in Congress would have fiercely fought an executive order for an integrated military.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] By contrast, most of the defense-related industry was in the Northeast, the Midwest, and California, so executive Order 8802 had only limited impact in the South.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] The proposed march on Washington was a turning point in the civil rights movement.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] One Black newspaper wrote at the time, "it demonstrated to the Doubting Thomases among us that only mass action can pry open the doors that have been erected against America's Black minority".
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Before 1941, Black leaders had generally sought to lobby white politicians to change the laws.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] After 1941, there was a tendency to bypass politicians and instead engage in protests.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Executive Order 8802 led to an exodus of Black people out of the South comparable to the Great Migration of the early 20th century.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] For example, in every month of 1942, about 10,000 Afro-Americans from the South, mostly from Texas and Louisiana, settled in the Los Angeles area, to take jobs in the well-paying aviation industry.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] The movement continued to gain momentum.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Unlike World War I, Randolph supported the war effort in World War II under the slogan "Double Victory", meaning victory over fascism abroad and racism at home.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1942, an estimated 18,000 Black people gathered at Madison Square Garden to hear Randolph kick off a campaign against discrimination in the military, war industries, government agencies, and labor unions.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1943, Randolph visited Memphis to launch a personal campaign for free speech after E.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Crump, a Democratic ally of Roosevelt, successfully used strong-arm and political pressure tactics to drive two prominent local Black Republicans, J.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Martin and Robert Church Jr., out of the city.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] After he came to Memphis, Crump denied Randolph venues and intimidated local Black leaders into declining speaking invitations by threatening them with jail.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] When Randolph urged Eleanor Roosevelt, who had friendly political ties with Crump, to do something to counter Crump's "fascist" denial of free speech, she refused.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Her reply to Randolph on December 18 read in full: "I referred your letter to a friend of mine when I received it and I am sorry it has not been answered before.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph and other activists continued to press for African Americans' rights.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1947, Randolph and Grant Reynolds renewed efforts to end discrimination in the armed services, forming the Committee Against Jim Crow in Military Service, later renamed the League for Non-Violent Civil disobedience.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Truman asked Congress for a peacetime draft law, Randolph urged young Black men to refuse to register.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Truman was vulnerable to defeat in 1948 and needed the support of the growing Black population in northern states, and he capitulated.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] On July 26, 1948, Truman began ending racial segregation in the armed forces with Executive Order 9981.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1950, along with NAACP Executive Secretary Roy Wilkins and National Jewish Community Relations Advisory Council leader Arnold Aronson, Randolph founded the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights (LCCR), which became a major civil rights coalition.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] It coordinated a national legislative campaign on behalf of every major civil rights law since 1957.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph and Rustin also formed an important alliance with Martin Luther King Jr. in 1957, when schools in the south resisted school integration after *Brown v.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph and King organized the Prayer Pilgrimage for Freedom.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1958 and 1959, Randolph organized Youth Marches for Integrated Schools in Washington, D.C.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] At the same time, he arranged for Rustin to teach King to organize peaceful demonstrations in Alabama and form alliances with progressive whites.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] The protests, directed by James Bevel in cities such as Birmingham and Montgomery, provoked violent backlash by police and the local Ku Klux Klan in 1963, which was captured on television and broadcast worldwide.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Rustin later said that Birmingham "was one of television's finest hours.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph finally realized his vision for a March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom on August 28, 1963.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] It attracted between 200,000 and 300,000 to the nation's capital.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] The rally is often remembered as the high point of the Civil Rights Movement, and it did help keep the issue in the public consciousness.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] But when President Kennedy was assassinated three months later, civil rights legislation stalled in the Senate.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Johnson, the Civil Rights Act finally passed.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] King and Bevel deserve great credit for these legislative victories, but the importance of Randolph's contributions to the Civil Rights Movement is large.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph avoided speaking publicly about his religious beliefs to avoid alienating his diverse constituencies.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Though he is sometimes identified as an atheist, particularly by his detractors, Randolph identified with the African Methodist Episcopal Church he was raised in.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] He pioneered the use of prayer protests, which became a key tactic of the civil rights movement.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] In 1973, he signed the *Humanist Manifesto II*.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph died in his Manhattan apartment on May 16, 1979.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] For several years before his death, he had a heart condition and high blood pressure.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] He had no known living relatives, as his wife Lucille had died in 1963, before the March on Washington.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Randolph had a significant impact on the Civil Rights Movement from the 1930s onward.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] The Montgomery bus boycott in Alabama was directed by E.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Nixon, who had been a member of the BSCP and was influenced by Randolph's methods of nonviolent confrontation.
[src:african-american-culture/a-philip-randolph] Nationwide, the Civil Rights Movement in the 1950s and 1960s used tactics pioneered by Randolph, such as encouraging African Americans to vote as a bloc, mass voter registration, and training activists for nonviolent direct action.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] The cast is led by Howard Rollins and Adolph Caesar.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Other actors include Art Evans, David Alan Grier, Larry Riley, David Harris, Robert Townsend, and Patti LaBelle.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Denzel Washington, still at the beginning of his career, appears in a supporting role.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Several actors reprise their roles from the stage version.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] The film premiered at the 1984 Toronto International Film Festival and was both a critical and commercial success.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] It received three Academy Award nominations: Best Picture, Best Adapted Screenplay and Best Supporting Actor for Adolph Caesar.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] The film was ranked by the National Board of Review as one of the 10 best films of 1984, and it won the Golden Prize at the 14th Moscow International Film Festival.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] In 1944 during World War II, Vernon Waters, a master sergeant in a company of Black soldiers, is shot to death with a .45 caliber pistol outside Fort Neal, a segregated Army base in Louisiana.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Captain Richard Davenport, a Black officer from the Judge Advocate General's Corps, is sent to investigate.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Most assume Waters was killed by the local Ku Klux Klan, but others are doubtful.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Even Captain Taylor, the only White officer who wants the killers prosecuted, is uncooperative and patronizing, fearing a Black officer will have little success.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Davenport soon discovers that whenever the Klan murders Black soldiers, they strip them of their military insignia, whereas the body of Sgt.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Waters was found wearing an intact uniform.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Davenport learns that Waters's company was officially part of the 221st Chemical Smoke Generator Battalion.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] They are kept on the Home Front and assigned menial jobs.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Most are former baseball players from the Negro leagues, grouped to play ball with Waters as manager.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Private James Wilkie, a former sergeant Waters busted for being drunk on duty, describes Waters as a combat veteran who was awarded with the Croix de Guerre by the Third French Republic during the First World War.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] He also says that Waters was a strict disciplinarian but a fair non-commissioned officer (NCO) who interacted well with his men, especially baseball pitcher and jazz musician C.J.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Private Peterson reveals Waters's tyrannical nature and his disgust with Black soldiers from the rural South who lacked education or who spoke in Gullah language.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Peterson recalls how he thrashed Waters when the sergeant berated the men after a winning game.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Interviewing other soldiers, Davenport learns that Waters charged Memphis with the murder of a White MP after a search conducted by Wilkie turned up a recently discharged pistol under his bunk.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Waters provoked Memphis into hitting him, and while the murder charge was dismissed, Memphis was charged with striking a superior officer.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Davenport interrogates Memphis's best friend, Corporal Bernard Cobb.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Cobb recalls visiting Memphis in the brig, where he told Cobb of a visit in which Waters admitted the planted gun was part of a frame-up.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Waters viewed "Geechees", as he termed uneducated southern Blacks like Memphis, as an obstacle to racial equality and the success of the future African American upper class.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Davenport also learns from Cobb that Memphis, who suffered from claustrophobia, hanged himself while awaiting his court-martial.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] In protest, the baseball team threw the season's last game.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Taylor disbanded the team, and the players were reassigned to the 221st.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Davenport learns that racist White officers, Captain Wilcox and Lieutenant Byrd, had an altercation with Waters shortly before his death.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] While being interrogated by Davenport and Taylor at the officer's club, Wilcox and Byrd admit to assaulting a guilt-ridden Waters after he confronted them in a drunken tirade.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] They admit that they would have killed him, but only men on guard duty are issued .45 ammunition when the unit is on bivouac.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Immediately after learning of Waters's murder, both officers turned in their sidearms, and ballistics testing cleared them.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Davenport interrogates Wilkie, who admits he planted the gun under Memphis's bunk on Waters's orders.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Wilkie also reveals that Waters had told him the real reasons for his hatred of Gullah-speaking southern Blacks like Memphis.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] While serving with the American Expeditionary Forces (AEF) in France during World War I, a Black soldier in Waters's unit had, at the urging of racist White doughboys, humiliated them all by dressing up and acting like a monkey in front of French women at a cabaret.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] In retaliation, Waters and his enraged fellow Black doughboys slit the soldier's throat.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Davenport demands to know why Waters did not also frame Peterson after their fight.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Wilkie explains that Waters liked Peterson, as he spoke proper English and stood up for himself.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Davenport has Wilkie arrested just as the 221st is about to be shipped out to join the fight overseas.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Realizing Peterson and Smalls were on guard duty the night of the murder and thus had been issued .45 ammunition, Davenport interrogates Smalls.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] He confesses to watching as Peterson fatally shot Waters, claiming it was "justice" for Memphis and for all Black people.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Taylor congratulates Davenport on the arrests of Wilkie, Peterson, and Smalls, admitting that he will have to become accustomed to Negroes being commissioned officers.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Meanwhile, the platoon marches in preparation for their deployment to the European theater of war.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Jewison and many of the cast members worked for scale or less under a tight budget with Columbia Pictures.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] "No one really wanted to make this movie... a black story, it was based on World War II, and those themes were not popular at the box office", according to Jewison.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Warner Bros. turned it down, as did Universal and Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Columbia's Frank Price read the screenplay and was deeply interested, but the studio was hesitant about its commercial value, so Jewison offered to do the film for a $5 million budget and no salary.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] When the Directors Guild of America insisted he must have a fee, he agreed to take the lowest possible amount.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] The film ended up grossing $22.1 million.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Rollins, Jr. had just received an Oscar nomination for his role in *Ragtime* and was cast as the lead.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Most of the cast came from Broadway careers, but only Adolph Caesar, Denzel Washington, Larry Riley and William Allen Young appeared in both the movie and the original off-Broadway play with the Negro Ensemble Company in the New York City version.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] In a 1985 interview with the Los Angeles Times, Caesar stated, while crafting the character of Waters, he drew on his frustrating experiences with both racism and ignorance in Classical theatre, "I’d studied Shakespeare to death.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] I knew more about Shakespeare than Shakespeare knew about himself.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] After I did one season at a Shakespearean repertory company, a director said to me, ‘You have a marvelous voice.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Bill Clinton (then Governor of Arkansas) dropped by during the shooting.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] He became very enthused about the project and later helped by providing the Arkansas Army National Guard in full regalia for a grand scene, since Jewison could not afford to pay an army of extras.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Production was completed with their help at Fort Chaffee United States Army Ready Reserve base at Fort Smith.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Fuller had said Herman Melville's novella *Billy Budd* inspired the play.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] The film holds a 91% rating on Rotten Tomatoes from a sample of 22 critics.
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] The site's consensus reads, "A meticulously crafted murder mystery with incisive observations about race in America, *A Soldier's Story* benefits from a roundly excellent ensemble and Charles Fuller's politically urgent screenplay".
[src:african-american-culture/a-soldier-s-story] Metacritic, which uses a weighted average, assigned the film a score of 66 out of 100, based on 10 critics, indicating "generally favorable" reviews.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Aaron Douglas was born and raised in Topeka, Kansas, on May 26, 1899, to Aaron Douglas Sr, a baker from Tennessee, and Elizabeth Douglas, a homemaker and amateur artist from Alabama.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] His passion for art derived from admiring his mother's drawings.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] He attended Topeka High School, during which he worked for Skinner's Nursery and Union Pacific material yard, and graduated in 1917.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] After high school, Douglas moved to Detroit, Michigan, and held various jobs, including working as a plasterer and molding sand for automobile radiators at the Cadillac factory.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] During this time, he attended free classes at the Detroit Museum of Art.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Douglas travelled further eastward, through East St.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Louis to Dunkirk in upstate New York, working at the Essex Glass factory to earn money for college.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] He went on to attend college at the University of Nebraska in 1918.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] While there, Douglas worked as a busboy to finance his education.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] When the United States entered World War I, Douglas attempted to join the Student Army Training Corps (SATC) at the University of Nebraska, but was dismissed.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Historians have speculated that this dismissal was related to the racially segregated climate of American society and the military.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] He then transferred for a short time to the University of Minnesota, where he volunteered for the SATC and attained the rank of corporal.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] After the signing of the armistice, he returned to the University of Nebraska, where he received a Bachelor of Fine Arts degree in 1922.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] After graduating, Douglas worked as a waiter for the Union Pacific Railroad until 1923, when he secured a job teaching visual arts at Lincoln High School in Kansas City, Missouri, staying there until 1925.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] During his time in Kansas City, he exchanged letters with Alta Sawyer, his future wife, about his plans beyond teaching in a high-school setting.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] He wanted to take his art career to Paris, France, as many of his aspiring artist peers did.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] In 1925, Douglas intended to pass through Harlem, New York, on his way to Paris to advance his art career.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] He was convinced to stay in Harlem and develop his art during the height of the Harlem Renaissance, influenced by the writings of Alain Locke about the importance of Harlem for aspiring African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] While in Harlem, Douglas studied under Winold Reiss, a German portraitist who encouraged him to work with African-centric themes to create a sense of unity between African Americans with art; Douglas was included in Alain Locke's 1925 anthology *The New Negro* as Reiss's pupil.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Du Bois, then-editor at *The Crisis*, a monthly journal of the NAACP, and became art editor himself briefly in 1927.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Johnson, then-editor at *Opportunity*, the official publication of the National Urban League.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] These illustrations focused on articles about lynching and segregation, and theater and jazz.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] His illustrations also featured in the periodicals *Vanity Fair* and *Theatre Arts Monthly* and made the cover of the only issue of the African-American avantgarde magazine *Fire!!*.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] In 1927, Douglas was asked to create the first of his murals at Club Ebony, which highlighted Harlem nightlife.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] In 1928, Douglas received a one-year Barnes Foundation Fellowship in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, where Albert C.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Barnes, philanthropist and founder of the Barnes Foundation, supported him in studying the collection of Modernist paintings and African art.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] In addition, he was commissioned by Bennett College for Women in Greensboro, North Carolina, to create a mural with Harriet Tubman as its primary figure.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] He then moved in 1931 for one year to Paris, France, where he received training in sculpture and painting at the Académie Scandinave.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Douglas returned to Harlem in the mid-1930s to work on his mural painting techniques.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Having joined the American Communist Party at some point upon return, he began to explore more political topics within his art as well.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] In 1934, he was commissioned by New York's 135th Street YMCA to paint a mural on their building, as well as by the Public Works Administration to paint his most acclaimed mural cycle, *Aspects of Negro Life,* for the Countee Cullen Branch of New York Public Library.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] He used these murals to inform his audiences of the place of African Americans throughout America's history and its present society.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Douglas created a similar series of murals, which included *Into Bondage* (1936), for the Texas Centennial Exposition in Dallas in 1936.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] During the height of his commissioned work as a muralist, Douglas served as president of the Harlem Artists Guild in 1935, an organization designed to create a network of young artists in New York City to provide support, inspiration, and to help out young artists during the Harlem Renaissance.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] In 1937, the Rosenwald Foundation awarded Douglas a travel fellowship to go to the American South and visit primarily Black universities, including Fisk University in Nashville, Tennessee, the Tuskegee Institute in Alabama, and Dillard University in New Orleans, Louisiana.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] In 1938, he again received a travel fellowship from the Rosenwald Foundation to go to the Dominican Republic and Haiti to develop a series of watercolors depicting the life of these Caribbean islands.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Upon returning to the United States in 1940, he worked at Fisk University in Nashville, while attending Columbia University Teacher’s College in New York City.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] He received his Master of Arts degree in 1944, and moved to Nashville, to found and sit as the chairman of the Art Department at Fisk.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] During his tenure as a professor in the Art Department, he was the founding director of the Carl Van Vechten Gallery of Fine Arts, which included both White and African-American art in an effort to educate students on being an artist in a segregated American South.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Douglas used his experiences as an artist in the Harlem Renaissance to inspire his students to expand on the movements of African-American art.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] He also encouraged his students to study African-American history to fully understand the necessity for African-American art in predominantly White-American society.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Douglas retired from teaching in the Art Department at Fisk University in 1966.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Aaron Douglas died in Nashville on February 2, 1979, at the age of 79.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Aaron Douglas pioneered the African-American modernist movement by combining aesthetic with ancient African traditional art.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] He set the stage for future African-American artists to utilize elements of African and African-American history alongside racial themes present in society.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] In 2007, the Spencer Museum of Art organized an exhibition titled *Aaron Douglas: African-American Modernist*.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] It was held in Lawrence, Kansas, at the Spencer Museum of Art between September 8 to December 2, 2007, and traveled to the Frist Center for the Visual Arts in Nashville, Tennessee, from January 18 to April 13, 2008.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] It was then on display at the Smithsonian American Art Museum in Washington, D.C,. between May 9 and August 3, 2008.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Finally, it traveled to the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture in New York, New York, from August 30 to November 30, 2008.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] An exhaustive catalog of this exhibition was put together through collaboration between Spencer Museum of Art and The University of Kansas, with the title *Aaron Douglas: African American Modernist*.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Douglas's work was featured in the 2015 exhibition *We Speak: Black Artists in Philadelphia, 1920s-1970s* at the Woodmere Art Museum.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] In 2016, with the opening of the National Museum of African American History and Culture, an archive of artworks created by or having to do with Aaron Douglas became available on their website.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Users can access the full references of these pieces of art to determine the creation date, subject of the art, and its current residence.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Aaron Douglas developed two art styles during his career: first as a traditional portraitist, then as a muralist and illustrator.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Influenced by having worked with Winold Reiss, Douglas incorporated African themes into his artwork to create a connection between Africans and African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] His work is described as being abstract, in that he portrayed the universality of the African-American people through song, dance, imagery and poetry.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Through his murals and illustrations for various publications, he addressed social issues connected with race and segregation in the United States, and was one of the first African-American visual artists to utilize African-centered imagery.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] His work features silhouettes of men and women, often in black and white.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] His human depictions have characteristically flat shapes that are angular and long, with slits for eyes.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Often, his female figures are drawn in a crouched position or moving as if they are dancing in a traditional African way.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] He adopted elements of West African masks and sculptures into his own art, with a technique that utilized cubism to simplify his figures into lines and planes.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] He employed a narrow range of color, tone and value, most often using greens, browns, mauves, and blacks, with his human forms in darker shades of the present colors of the painting.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] He created emotional impact with subtle gradations of color, often using concentric circles to influence the viewer to focus on a specific part of the painting.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] His artwork is two-dimensional, and his human figures are faceless, allowing their forms to be symbolic and general, so as to create a sense of unity between Africans and African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] Douglas’ paintings include semitransparent silhouettes to portray the struggle of African Americans and their relative successes in various aspects of social life.
[src:african-american-culture/aaron-douglas-artist] His work is described as unique in creating a link between African Americans and their African ancestry through visual elements that are rooted in African art, and thus give the African-American experience a symbolic aesthetic.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] Alkalimat is the great-great-grandson of Free Frank McWorter.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] Born as Gerald Arthur McWorter in Chicago's Cook County Hospital, he lived with his family in the Frances Cabrini Houses until 1953, when they moved to the city's West Side.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] Alkalimat attended Ottawa University, where he earned a B.A. in sociology and philosophy in 1963.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] He completed his M.A. in sociology at the University of Chicago in 1966, and earned a Ph.D. in sociology there in 1974.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] During the late 1960s, he helped create the Institute of the Black World (IBW) in Atlanta with professors Vincent Harding and Stephen Henderson and other student activists, including Howard Dodson, A.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] Spellman, William Strickland, and Council Taylor.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] The IBW became "the most dynamic black 'think tank' of the era", according to Peniel E.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] Joseph, assistant professor of Africana studies at Stony Brook University.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] In the early 1970s, Alkalimat established Peoples College, a black nationalist think tank.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] Acknowledged as a founder of Black Studies, he wrote *Introduction to Afro-American Studies: A Peoples College Primer*, first published in 1984, which has become a popular text and gone through several editions.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] Alkalimat helped to organize the Illinois Council for Black Studies, and in 1982 he hosted the annual meeting of the National Council for Black Studies (NCBS).
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] He was elected the NCBS chairman, but the organization's board questioned the results and called for a new election the following year to determine whether Alkalimat's ascension to the post was legitimate.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] In an election that many members considered confusing, Alkalimat was voted out.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] New voting rules were adopted by the board that made the results retroactive, stripping Alkalimat of his chairmanship.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] In 1991, Alkalimat wrote *Malcolm X for Beginners*.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] He and his publisher, Writers and Readers Press, were sued by Betty Shabazz, the widow of Malcolm X, and Pathfinder Press, which has exclusive rights to publish Malcolm X's speeches.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] Shabazz and Pathfinder alleged the book contained quotations from Malcolm X without permission.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] Alkalimat and his publisher said that the book's quotations were permitted under the fair use doctrine.
[src:african-american-culture/abdul-alkalimat] The matter was settled out of court, with Alkalimat relinquishing all royalties from the book.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-American culture has been influential on American and global culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-Americans have made major contributions to American literature, music, visual art, media, politics, science, business, and cuisine.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Notably, African-American musical forms such as jazz, rock and roll, and hip-hop have been among the United States' most successful cultural exports.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African American culture has always been defined, in part, by the struggle to resist and overcome racist laws and practices, including but not limited to enslavement, oppressive legislation like discriminatory Jim Crow laws, and societal segregation, as well as overt denial of basic human rights.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Racism has caused African-Americans to be excluded from many aspects of American life throughout American history, and these experiences have profoundly influenced African-American culture, and informed how African Americans choose to interact with the broader American society.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] A heritage of West and Central African stories, proverbs, wordplay, and legends has informed African-American culture since the time of slavery.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Religious and spiritual life have informed many aspects of African American culture, including the Civil Rights Movement.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Throughout the year, African Americans observe various holidays.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In the United States, Black History Month is celebrated every February to honor the rich history and contributions of African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Juneteenth, observed on June 19, commemorates the end of slavery in the U.S.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Additionally, many African Americans celebrate Kwanzaa from December 26 to January 1.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African American culture is not simply defined by race or historical struggle but is deeply rooted in shared practices, identity, and community.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Most African Americans are the descendants of enslaved people who lived within the boundaries of the present United States.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In addition, African Americans that are American Descendants of Slavery (ADOS) are primarily of West African and coastal Central African ancestry, with varying amounts of Western European and Native American ancestry.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Roughly one-in-five Black people in the U.S. are immigrants or children of Black immigrants.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] While some Black immigrants or their children may also come to identify with African Americans, Black immigrants to the U.S. are not part of the African American ethnic group.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The majority of first-generation immigrants from Africa prefer to identify with their nation of origin.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] There is some recent research which shows that some Black immigrants to the US resist assimilation to reduce exposure to racial discrimination faced by native-born African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African American culture emerged amid systemic anti-Black racism in the United States, characterized by widespread violence, oppression and exclusion driven by white supremacy during the European colonial era.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] From the earliest days of American slavery in the 17th century, slave holders sought to exercise control over their people who were forced into slavery by attempting to strip them of their African culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Slave holders deliberately tried to repress independent political or cultural organization in order to deal with the many slave rebellions or acts of resistance that took place in the United States, Brazil, Haiti, and the Dutch Guyanas.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Various African traditions provided a foundation for the spiritual practices of enslaved individuals, who blended ancestral beliefs with Christianity to create various forms of worship.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] This cultural resilience was evident in slave rebellions, which challenged the institution of slavery and fostered a sense of community and shared identity among African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The civil rights movement emerged as a powerful continuation of this struggle.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] This historical legacy influenced contemporary African-American families and shaped their values, community structures, and approaches to political engagement, with the enduring economic impacts of systemic inequality driving a commitment to empowerment and social change.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The imprint of Africa is evident in politics, economics, language, music, hairstyles, fashion, dance, religion, cuisine, and worldview.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Throughout all of this, African Americans created their own culture and history in the United States.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In turn, African-American culture has had a pervasive and transformative impact on many elements of mainstream American culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] This process of mutual creative exchange is called creolization.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Over time, the culture of African slaves and their descendants has had a ubiquitous impact on the dominant American culture and on world culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The holders of enslaved trapped people (slaves) limited or prohibited their education, the fear was that education might empower the people, and inspire or enable emancipatory ambitions.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-based oral traditions became the primary means of preserving history, mores, and other cultural information among the people.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] This was consistent with the *griot* practices of oral history in many native African culture and other cultures that did not rely on the written word.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Many of these cultural elements have been passed from generation to generation through storytelling.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The folktales provided African-Americans the opportunity to inspire and educate one another.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Modernity and migration of African-American communities to the North has had a history of placing strain on the retention of African-American cultural practices and traditions.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The urban and radically different spaces in which black culture was being produced raised fears in anthropologists and sociologists that the southern African-American folk aspect of black popular culture were at risk of being lost within history.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Other aspects of African-American oral tradition include the dozens, signifying, trash talk, rhyming, semantic inversion and word play, many of which have found their way into mainstream American popular culture and become international phenomena.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] During slavery, African Americans adapted these linguistic traditions as a form of covert resistance and survival.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Spoken-word poetry is another example of how the African-American oral tradition has influenced modern popular culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Spoken-word artists employ the same techniques as African-American preachers including movement, rhythm, and audience participation.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Rap music from the 1980s and beyond has been cited as an extension of African oral culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The first major public recognition of African-American culture occurred during the Harlem Renaissance pioneered by Alain Locke.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In the 1920s and 1930s, African-American music, literature, and art gained wide notice.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Authors such as Zora Neale Hurston and Nella Larsen and poets such as Langston Hughes, Claude McKay, and Countee Cullen wrote works describing the African-American experience.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Jazz, swing, blues and other musical forms entered American popular music.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-American artists such as William H.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Johnson, Aaron Douglas, and Palmer Hayden created unique works of art featuring African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The Harlem Renaissance was also a time of increased political involvement for African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Among the notable African-American political movements founded in the early 20th century are the Universal Negro Improvement Association and the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The Nation of Islam, a notable quasi-Islamic religious movement, also began in the early 1930s.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The Black Power movement of the 1960s and 1970s followed in the wake of the non-violent Civil Rights Movement.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The movement promoted racial pride and ethnic cohesion in contrast to the focus on integration of the Civil Rights Movement, and adopted a more militant posture in the face of racism.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] It also inspired a new renaissance in African-American literary and artistic expression generally referred to as the African-American or "Black Arts Movement".
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The works of popular recording artists such as Nina Simone ("Young, Gifted and Black") and The Impressions ("Keep On Pushing"), as well as the poetry, fine arts, and literature of the time, shaped and reflected the growing racial and political consciousness.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Among the most prominent writers of the African-American Arts Movement were poet Nikki Giovanni; poet and publisher Don L.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Lee, who later became known as Haki Madhubuti; poet and playwright Leroi Jones, later known as Amiri Baraka; and Sonia Sanchez.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] During the African American cultural Movement, Melvin Charles and Gleason T Jackson created the Black American Heritage Flag (also known as the African American Heritage Flag) in 1967 for Black Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] It is used today as an ethnic flag that represents the African American people.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] During this time, there was a resurgence of interest in elements of African culture within African-American culture that had been suppressed or devalued to conform to Eurocentric America.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Natural hairstyles, such as the afro, and African clothing, such as the dashiki, gained popularity.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] More importantly, the African-American aesthetic encouraged personal pride and political awareness among African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Music in African-American culture extends far beyond the realms of performance and consumption; it is deeply rooted in community participation and interaction.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The act of music-making—actively engaging with music in various forms—includes singing together in churches, participating in call-and-response patterns, dancing, and even informal music-making in social settings.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In African-American churches, gospel music serves as a form of worship and a collective spiritual experience.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Congregants engage fully in music-making, responding to the choir with shouts of affirmation, clapping, and even dancing.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The tradition of call-and-response, which originated in African and African-American spirituals, is a key feature in many genres, including gospel, jazz, and hip-hop.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The dynamic interaction between performer and audience blurs the line between the two and invites the entire community to participate.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In jazz, for instance, improvisation between musicians can be viewed as a form of music-making where the performers engage in a musical dialogue that often involves audience feedback and interaction.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Similarly, early hip-hop culture emphasized the participatory nature of music-making, with community members engaging through freestyle rap battles, breakdancing, and DJing.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] These music-making practices emphasize the active role of music as a social connector, shape cultural identity, and foster communal bonds.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-American music is rooted in the typically polyrhythmic music of the ethnic groups of Africa, specifically those in the Western, Sahelean, and Central and Southern regions.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African oral traditions, nurtured in slavery, encouraged the use of music to pass on history, teach lessons, ease suffering, and relay messages.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The African pedigree of African-American music is evident in some common elements: call and response, syncopation, percussion, improvisation, swung notes, blue notes, the use of falsetto, melisma, and complex multi-part harmony.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] During slavery, Africans in America blended traditional European hymns with African elements to create spirituals.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The banjo was the first African derived instrument to be played and built in the United States.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Slaveholders discovered African-American slaves used drums to communicate.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] As far back as the 1700s, after drums were outlawed after the Stono Rebellion in South Carolina, African Americans created hamboning, patting their bodies in order to make their music.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Many African Americans sing "Lift Every Voice and Sing" in addition to the American national anthem, "The Star-Spangled Banner", or in lieu of it.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Written by James Weldon Johnson and John Rosamond Johnson in 1900 to be performed for the birthday of Abraham Lincoln, the song was, and continues to be, a popular way for African Americans to recall past struggles and express ethnic solidarity, faith, and hope for the future.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The song was adopted as the "Negro National Anthem" by the NAACP in 1919.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Many African-American children are taught the song at school, church or by their families.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] "Lift Ev'ry Voice and Sing" traditionally is sung immediately following, or instead of, "The Star-Spangled Banner" at events hosted by African-American churches, schools, and other organizations.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In the 19th century, as the result of the blackface minstrel show, African-American music entered mainstream American society.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] By the early 20th century, several musical forms with origins in the African-American community had transformed American popular music.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Aided by the technological innovations of radio and phonograph records, ragtime, jazz, blues, and swing also became popular overseas, and the 1920s became known as the Jazz Age.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The early 20th century also saw the creation of the first African-American Broadway shows, films such as King Vidor's *Hallelujah!*, and operas such as George Gershwin's *Porgy and Bess*.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The African-American Cultural Movement of the 1960s and 1970s fueled the growth of funk, soul, disco, and later hip hop forms with sub-genres of hip hop to include; rap, hip house, new jack swing, and go-go.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] House music was created in black communities in Chicago in the 1980s.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Hip hop and contemporary R&B would become a multicultural movement, however, it still remained important to many African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In the 21st century, African-American music has achieved unprecedented levels of mainstream acceptance and influence in American popular music.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] This is evident from its dominant performance on the Billboard charts, where genres such as hip-hop and R&B, deeply rooted in African-American culture, have surpassed pop in terms of streaming and sales.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The impact of African-American artists on contemporary music, fashion, and cultural trends is significant, with figures like Beyoncé, Kendrick Lamar, and Drake shaping the industry and reflecting its broad appeal across diverse audiences.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Furthermore, the integration of African-American musical styles into mainstream media has been highlighted by high-profile collaborations and genre-blending successes, such as Lil Nas X’s "Old Town Road," which achieved historic chart success by merging hip-hop with country music.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Streaming platforms like Spotify and Apple Music also show the substantial engagement and commercial success of African-American music across various demographics.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In addition to continuing to develop newer musical forms, modern artists have also started a rebirth of older genres in the form of genres such as neo soul and modern funk-inspired groups.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] As of November 2018, the leading music genre listened to by African Americans is Rhythm and Blues (62%), followed by Hip Hop (39%), Gospel (26%), Rap (21%), Soul/Funk (19%), and Jazz (18%).
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-American dance, like other aspects of African-American culture, finds its earliest roots in the dances of the hundreds of African ethnic groups that made up the enslaved African population in the Americas as well as in traditional folk dances from Europe.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Dance in the African tradition, and thus in the tradition of slaves, was a part of both everyday life and special occasions.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Many of these traditions such as get down, ring shouts, Akan Line Dancing and other elements of African body language survive as elements of modern dance.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In the 19th century, African-American dance began to appear in minstrel shows.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] These shows often presented African Americans as caricatures for ridicule to large audiences.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The first African-American dance to become popular with white dancers was the cakewalk in 1891.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Later dances to follow in this tradition include the Charleston, the Lindy Hop, the Jitterbug and the swing.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] During the Harlem Renaissance, African-American Broadway shows such as *Shuffle Along* helped to establish and legitimize African-American dancers.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-American dance forms such as tap, a combination of African and European influences, gained widespread popularity thanks to dancers such as Bill Robinson and were used by leading white choreographers, who often hired African-American dancers.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Contemporary African-American dance is descended from these earlier forms and also draws influence from African and Caribbean dance forms.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Groups such as the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater have continued to contribute to the growth of this form.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Modern popular dance in America is also greatly influenced by African-American dance.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] American popular dance has also drawn many influences from African-American dance most notably in the hip-hop genre.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] One of the uniquely African-American forms of dancing, turfing, emerged from social and political movements in the East Bay in the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Turfing is a hood dance and a response to the loss of African-American lives, police brutality, and race relations in Oakland, California.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The dance is an expression of Blackness, and one that integrates concepts of solidarity, social support, peace, and the discourse of the state of black people in our current social structures.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Twerking is an African-American dance similar to dances from Africa in Côte d'Ivoire, Senegal, Somalia and the Congo.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] From its early origins in slave communities, through the end of the 20th century, African-American art has made a vital contribution to the art of the United States.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] During the period between the 17th century and the early 19th century, art took the form of small drums, quilts, wrought-iron figures, and ceramic vessels in the southern United States.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] These artifacts have similarities with comparable crafts in West and Central Africa.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In contrast, African-American artisans like the New England–based engraver Scipio Moorhead and the Baltimore portrait painter Joshua Johnson created art that was conceived in a thoroughly western European fashion.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] During the 19th century, Harriet Powers made quilts in rural Georgia, United States that are now considered among the finest examples of 19th-century Southern quilting.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Later in the 20th century, the women of Gee's Bend developed a distinctive, bold, and sophisticated quilting style based on traditional African-American quilts with a geometric simplicity that developed separately but was like that of Amish quilts and modern art.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] After the American Civil War, museums and galleries began more frequently to display the work of African-American artists.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Cultural expression in mainstream venues was still limited by the dominant European aesthetic and by racial prejudice.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] To increase the visibility of their work, many African-American artists traveled to Europe where they had greater freedom.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] It was not until the Harlem Renaissance that more European Americans began to pay attention to African-American art in America.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] During the 1920s, artists such as Richmond Barthé, Aaron Douglas, Augusta Savage, and photographer James Van Der Zee became well known for their work.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] During the Great Depression, new opportunities arose for these and other African-American artists under the WPA.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In later years, other programs and institutions, such as the New York City-based Harmon Foundation, helped to foster African-American artistic talent.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Augusta Savage, Elizabeth Catlett, Lois Mailou Jones, Romare Bearden, Jacob Lawrence, and others exhibited in museums and juried art shows, and built reputations and followings for themselves.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In the 1950s and 1960s, there were very few widely accepted African-American artists.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Despite this, The Highwaymen, a loose association of 27 African-American artists from Ft.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Pierce, Florida, created idyllic, quickly realized images of the Florida landscape and peddled some 50,000 of them from the trunks of their cars.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] They sold their art directly to the public rather than through galleries and art agents, thus receiving the name "The Highwaymen".
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Rediscovered in the mid-1990s, today they are recognized as an important part of American folk history.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Their artwork is widely collected by enthusiasts and original pieces can easily fetch thousands of dollars in auctions and sales.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The Black Arts Movement of the 1960s and 1970s was another period of resurgent interest in African-American art.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] During this period, several African-American artists gained national prominence, among them Lou Stovall, Ed Love, Charles White, and Jeff Donaldson.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Donaldson and a group of African-American artists formed the Afrocentric collective AfriCOBRA, which remains in existence today.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The sculptor Martin Puryear, whose work has been acclaimed for years, was being honored with a 30-year retrospective of his work at the Museum of Modern Art in New York in November 2007.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Notable contemporary African-American artists include Willie Cole, David Hammons, Eugene J.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Martin, Mose Tolliver, Reynold Ruffins, the late William Tolliver, and Kara Walker.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In Charleston, South Carolina, thirteen colonoware from the 18th century were found with folded strip roulette decorations.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] From the time of colonial America until the 19th century in the United States, African-Americans and their enslaved African ancestors, as well as Native Americans who were enslaved and not enslaved, were creating colonoware of this pottery style.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Roulette decorated pottery likely originated in West Africa and in the northern region of Central Africa amid 2000 BCE.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] More specifically, the pottery style for the Charleston colonoware may have been created by 18th century peoples (e.g., Kanuri people, Hausa people in Kano) of the Kanem–Bornu Empire.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Symbolisms from Africa may have served as identity markers for enslaved African-American creators of stoneware.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] For example, David Drake's signature marks (e.g., an "X", a slash) and well as Landrum crosses, which were developed by enslaved African Americans and appear similar to Kongo cosmograms, are such examples from Edgefield County, South Carolina.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-American literature has its roots in the oral traditions of African slaves in America.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The slaves used stories and fables in much the same way as they used music.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] These stories influenced the earliest African-American writers and poets in the 18th century such as Phillis Wheatley and Olaudah Equiano.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] These authors reached early high points by telling slave narratives.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] During the early 20th century Harlem Renaissance, numerous authors and poets, such as Langston Hughes, W.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Washington, grappled with how to respond to discrimination in America.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Authors during the Civil Rights Movement, such as Richard Wright, James Baldwin, and Gwendolyn Brooks wrote about issues of racial segregation, oppression, and other aspects of African-American life.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Such works have achieved both best-selling and/or award-winning status.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-American films typically feature an African-American cast and are targeted at an African-American audience.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] More recently, Black films feature multicultural casts, and are aimed at multicultural audiences, even if American Blackness is essential to the storyline.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Baseball used to be a major sport among African Americans; however, basketball (particularly streetball) has replaced it to a substantial extent in recent decades.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Black athletes have achieved disproportionate success in some sports, and at the professional level, they constitute the majority of NFL and NBA athletes.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African Americans played a significant role in desegregating American society through sports.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] For example, baseball was segregated in the aftermath of the Civil War until Jackie Robinson broke the MLB color line in 1947.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In modern times, sports have been pursued by the poorer sections of the community as a way out of economic struggle.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Card games such as bid whist, spades, tonk, pitty-pat, and rummy are traditionally enjoyed by African Americans at familial gatherings.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] "Talkin' the board", or illegally providing one's partner with hidden information, is not allowed in any game.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Hand games that trickled from Africa are also prominent in Black American culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Double This, Double That, Mama Mama Can't You See, Slide Baby, Miss Mary Mack, Down, Down Baby, Rockin' Robin (Tweet), Down by the Banks of the Hanky Panky, and Shame, Shame, Shame are kinesthetic games enjoyed predominantly by young Black girls.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The African American Museum Movement emerged during the 1950s and 1960s to preserve the heritage of the African-American experience and to ensure its proper interpretation in American history.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Museums devoted to African-American history are found in many African-American neighborhoods.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Other prominent African-American museums include Chicago's DuSable Museum of African American History, and the National Museum of African American History and Culture, established in 2003 as part of the Smithsonian Institution in Washington, D.C.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The history of the involuntary manner in which African Americans arrived in the United States, coupled with 100 years of forced segregation from the dominant culture allowed for a protracted period where language was being formed and shaped outside the traditional patterns.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Most enslaved Africans brought to the Americas came from the West African coast.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The languages of this region, such as those from the Niger-Congo family, had a significant influence.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Some specific examples include the Wolof, Yoruba, Igbo and Mandé languages.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] There was also a large contingent from Central Africa, especially from regions where Bantu languages were spoken, such as Kongo (Kikongo), Mbundu and Swahili.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The native speakers of these and other languages were forced to quickly find a way to agree upon new words and phrases as a matter of survival, while also learning and integrating various dialects of American English which varied by region.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Over time a divergent form of English emerged.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Over the 246 years of chattel slavery in the southern US and societal segregation in the northern states, varied forms of English took root within the African American culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] An additional century of forced segregation and Jim Crow between 1865 and 1965 extended the period when African Americans, still not fully immersed in the broader society, did not experience the traditional process of adopting the dominant society's language.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Filtering the English they heard through their language systems and culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] West Africans were primarily (not exclusively) placed in non-field work in the upper southern colonies and West Central/Central Africans were primarily (not exclusively) placed in field based work in the lower southern colonies.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Africans in primarily non-field work typically had extensive interaction with Europeans in the early period, with cultural influence being bi-directional.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Colonies typically preferred certain African ethnic groups, some very selective (South Carolina for example), others a bit more loose but still maintained a level of preference (Virginia for example).
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] West Central and Central Africans brought with them a homogenous culture that superseded West African culture early on in establishing African-American culture, at a later point in history, West African influence displays itself in African-American culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Interaction between West Africans and West Central/Central Africans did occur, creating a lingua franca, however the culture of African Americans was heavily affected by the homogeneity and relatively isolated Bantu imported population.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Later influence from West Africa presents itself in African-American culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-American speech however is heavily based (but not exclusively, includes West Africa to some extent) in Bantu culture, as such, it is responsible for African Americans' language patterns, combining an African substrate with the topical usage of primarily non-African words.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] AAVE has its roots in the historical experiences of African Americans and plays a crucial role in cultural identity and expression.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] It has also significantly influenced mainstream American English, particularly through music, literature, and media.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Linguists and speakers of AAL (African American Language) have shown that the grammatical structure of AAL is Niger-Congo and that the cultural/relational patterns within the language that are of African origin characterize or color it.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] While AAVE is academically considered a legitimate dialect because of its logical structure, some of both whites and African Americans consider it slang or the result of a poor command of Standard American English, none of which is true; they are differences in languages.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Many African Americans who were born outside the American South still speak with hints of AAVE or southern dialect.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Inner-city African-American children who are isolated by speaking only AAVE sometimes have more difficulty with standardized testing and, after school, moving to the mainstream world for work.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] It is common for many speakers of AAVE to code switch between AAVE and Standard American English depending on the setting.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The Black Arts Movement, a cultural explosion of the 1960s, saw the incorporation of surviving cultural dress with elements from modern fashion and West African traditional clothing to create a uniquely African-American traditional style.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Kente cloth is the best known African textile.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] These colorful woven patterns, which exist in numerous varieties, were originally made by the Asante and Ewe peoples of Ghana and Togo.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Kente fabric also appears in a number of Western style fashions ranging from casual T-shirts to formal bow ties and cummerbunds.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Kente strips are often sewn into liturgical and academic robes or worn as stoles.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Since the Black Arts Movement, traditional African clothing has been popular amongst African Americans for both formal and informal occasions.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Other manifestations of traditional African dress in common evidence in African-American culture are vibrant colors, mud cloth, trade beads and the use of Adinkra motifs in jewelry and in couture and decorator fabrics.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Another common aspect of fashion in African-American culture involves the appropriate dress for worship in the Black church.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] It is expected in most churches that an individual present their best appearance for worship.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-American women in particular are known for wearing vibrant dresses and suits.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] An interpretation of a passage from the Christian Bible, "every woman who prays or prophesies with her head uncovered dishonors her head", has led to the tradition of wearing elaborate Sunday hats, sometimes known as "crowns".
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Hip hop fashion is popular with African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Grillz were made popular by African-American rapper Nelly.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Sagging pants was a part of African-American culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Air Jordan, a shoe brand named after former African-American basketball player Michael Jordan, is very popular among the African-American community.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-American fashion designers include Ann Lowe, Christopher John Rogers, Virgil Abloh and Kanye West.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Hair styling in African-American culture is greatly varied.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-American hair is typically composed of coiled curls, which range from tight to wavy.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Many women choose to wear their hair in its natural state.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Natural hair can be styled in a variety of ways, including the afro, twist outs, braid outs, and wash and go styles.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] It is a myth that natural hair presents styling problems or is hard to manage; this myth seems prevalent because mainstream culture has, for decades, attempted to get African-American women to conform to its standard of beauty (i.e., straight hair).
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] To that end, some women prefer straightening of the hair through the application of heat or chemical processes.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Although this can be a matter of personal preference, the choice is often affected by straight hair being a beauty standard in the West and the fact that hair type can affect employment.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] However, more and more women are wearing their hair in its natural state and receiving positive feedback.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Alternatively, the predominant and most socially acceptable practice for men is to leave one's hair natural.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Often, as men age and begin to lose their hair, the hair is either closely cropped, or the head is shaved completely free of hair.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] However, since the 1960s, natural hairstyles, such as the afro, braids, waves, fades, and dreadlocks, have been growing in popularity.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Despite their association with radical political movements and their vast difference from mainstream Western hairstyles, the styles have attained considerable, but certainly limited, social acceptance.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Maintaining facial hair is more prevalent among African-American men than in other male populations in the US.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In fact, the soul patch is so named because African-American men, particularly jazz musicians, popularized the style.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The preference for facial hair among African-American men is due partly to personal taste, but also because they are more prone than other ethnic groups to develop a condition known as *pseudofolliculitis barbae*, commonly referred to as *razor bumps*, many prefer not to shave.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Eurocentric beauty standards have widely shaped image.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In an effort to unlearn these sentiments rooted in colonialism and white supremacy, a movement has ensued that promotes natural Black beauty.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] This includes efforts toward promoting models with clearly defined African features; the mainstreaming of natural hairstyles; and, in women, fuller, more voluptuous body types.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Non-Black Americans have sometimes appropriated different hair braiding techniques and other forms of African-American hair.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Some African Americans use shea butter to moisture their skin and hair.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] While African Americans practice a number of religions, Black Protestant is by far the most prevalent (59%), followed by Evangelical Protestant (15%).
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The religious institutions of African-American Christians are commonly and collectively referred to as the black church.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] During the era of slavery, many slaves were stripped of their African belief systems and typically denied free religious practice, some forced to become Christians while others brought Christianity from Africa.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] However, slaves managed to hang on to some of their traditional African religious practices by integrating them into Christian worship during secret meetings.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] These practices, including dance, shouts, African rhythms, and enthusiastic singing, remain a large part of worship in the African-American church.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Instead, the African-American church focused on the message of equality and hopes for a better future.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Before and after emancipation, racial segregation in America prompted the development of organized African-American denominations.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The first of these was the AME Church founded by Richard Allen in 1787.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] After the Civil War, the merger of three smaller Baptist groups formed the National Baptist Convention.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] This organization is the largest African-American Christian Denomination and it is also the second largest Baptist denomination in the United States.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] An African-American church is not necessarily a separate denomination.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Several predominantly African-American churches exist as members of predominantly white denominations.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] African-American churches have served to provide African-American people with leadership positions and opportunities to organize that were denied to them by mainstream American society.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Because of this, African-American pastors became the bridge between the African-American and European American communities, a leadership position which enabled them to play a crucial role during the Civil Rights Movement.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Like many Christians, African-American Christians sometimes participate in or attend a Christmas play.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] *Black Nativity* by Langston Hughes is a re-telling of the classic Nativity story with gospel music.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Productions can be found in African-American theaters and churches all over the country.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Many first-generation slaves were often able to retain their Muslim identity, their descendants were not.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Slaves were either forcibly converted to Christianity as was the case in the Catholic lands or were besieged with gross inconveniences to their religious practice such as in the case of the Protestant American mainland.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Many former members of the Nation of Islam converted to Sunni Islam when Warith Deen Mohammed took control of the organization after his father's death in 1975 and taught its members the traditional form of Islam based on the Qur'an.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] A survey by the Council on American-Islamic Relations shows that 30% of Sunni Mosque attendees are African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In fact, most African-American Muslims are orthodox Muslims, as only 2% are of the Nation of Islam.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] There are 150,000 African Americans in the United States who practice Judaism.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Some of these are members of mainstream Jewish groups like the Reform, Conservative, or Orthodox branches of Judaism; others belong to non-mainstream Jewish groups like the Black Hebrew Israelites.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The Black Hebrew Israelites are a collection of African-American religious organizations whose practices and beliefs are partially derived from Judaism.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Their varied teachings often include the belief that African Americans are descended from the biblical Israelites.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In the last 10 to 15 years, studies have shown that there has been a major increase in the number of African-Americans who identify themselves as being Jewish.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Aside from Christianity, Islam, and Judaism, there are also African Americans who practice Buddhism and a number of other religions.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] There is a small but growing number of African Americans who participate in Syncretic Religions, such as Voodoo, Santería, Ifá and diasporic traditions like the Rastafari movement.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Many of them are immigrants or the descendants of immigrants from the Caribbean and South America, where these are practiced.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Because of religious practices, such as animal sacrifice, which are no longer common among the larger American religions, these groups may be negatively viewed and they are sometimes the victims of harassment.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] It must be stated, however, that since the Supreme Court judgement that was given to the Lukumi Babaluaye church of Florida in 1993, there has been no major legal challenge to their right to function as they see fit.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Spirituality is an important aspect of African American culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Hoodoo is a set of spiritual traditions with multiple aspects that include: Southern cultural practices from the Antebellum Era, rootwork and conjure, ancestor veneration, and rituals.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] These traditions were created as a means for enslaved Africans in the United States to understand the new world around them, with some elements having origins across various Central and West African ethnic groups.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Hoodoo incorporates beliefs from traditional African religions, such as the Kongo religion, as well as Islam, Christianity, and Indigenous American botanical traditions.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] In a 2008 Pew Forum survey, 12% of African Americans described themselves as being nothing in particular (11%), agnostic (1%), or atheist (<0.5%).
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] For most African Americans, the observance of life events follows the pattern of mainstream American culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] While African Americans and whites often lived to themselves for much of American history, both groups generally had the same perspective on American culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] There are some traditions that are unique to African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Some African Americans have created new rites of passage that are linked to African traditions.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Some pre-teen and teenage boys and girls take classes to prepare them for adulthood.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] These classes tend to focus on spirituality, responsibility, and leadership.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Many of these programs are modeled after traditional African ceremonies, with the focus largely on embracing African cultures.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] To this day, some African-American couples choose to "jump the broom" as a part of their wedding ceremony.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Some sources claim that this practice can be traced back to Ghana.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] However, other sources argue that the African-American tradition of "jumping the broom" is far more similar to the tradition in England.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Although, this tradition largely fell out of favor in the African-American community after the end of slavery, it has experienced a slight resurgence in recent years as some couples seek to reaffirm their African heritage.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Funeral traditions tend to vary based on a number of factors, including religion and location, but there are a number of commonalities.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Probably the most important part of death and dying in the African-American culture is the gathering of family and friends.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Either in the last days before death or shortly after death, typically any friends and family members that can be reached are notified.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] This gathering helps to provide spiritual and emotional support, as well as assistance in making decisions and accomplishing everyday tasks.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The spirituality of death is very important in African-American culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] A member of the clergy or members of the religious community, or both, are typically present with the family through the entire process.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Death is often viewed as transitory rather than final.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] Many services are called homegoings or homecomings, instead of funerals, based on the belief that the person is going home to the afterlife; "Returning to God" or the earth.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] The entire end of life process is generally treated as a celebration of the person's life, deeds and accomplishments—the "good things" rather than a mourning of loss.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p01] This is most notably demonstrated in the New Orleans jazz funeral tradition where upbeat music, dancing, and food encourage those gathered to be happy and celebrate the homegoing of a beloved friend.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] In studying of the African-American culture, food cannot be left out as one of the media to understand their traditions, religion, interaction, and social and cultural structures of their community.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Observing the ways they prepare their food and eat their food ever since the enslaved era reveals about the nature and identity of African-American culture in the United States.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Derek Hicks examines the origins of "gumbo", which is considered a soul food to many African Americans, in his reference to the intertwinement of food and culture in the African-American community.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] No written evidence is found historically about the gumbo or its recipes, so through the African-American nature of orally passing their stories and recipes down, gumbo came to represent their truly communal dish.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Gumbo is said to be "an invention of enslaved Africans and African Americans" in Louisiana.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The cultivation and use of many agricultural products in the United States, such as yams, peanuts, rice, okra, sorghum, indigo dyes, and cotton, can be traced to African influences.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African-American foods reflect creative responses to racial and economic oppression and poverty.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Soul food blends African, European, and Native American influences.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Dishes like fried chicken, collard greens, and cornbread are staples that have become integral components of American cuisine.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Under slavery, African Americans were not allowed to eat better cuts of meat, and after emancipation many were often too poor to afford them.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] During slavery, many African Americans would take these sorts of leftover ingredients from their white owners, often less desirable cuts of meats and vegetables, and prepare them into a dish that has consistency between stew and soup.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] By sharing this food in churches with a gathering of their people, they also shared experience, feelings, attachment, and a sense of unity that brings the community together.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Soul food, a hearty cuisine commonly associated with African Americans in the South (but also common to African Americans nationwide), makes creative use of inexpensive products procured through farming and subsistence hunting and fishing.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Pig intestines are boiled and sometimes battered and fried to make chitterlings, also known as "chitlins".
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Ham hocks and neck bones provide seasoning to soups, beans and boiled greens.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Other common foods, such as fried chicken and fish, macaroni and cheese, cornbread, and hoppin' john (black-eyed peas and rice) are prepared simply.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] When the African-American population was considerably more rural than it generally is today, rabbit, opossum, squirrel, and waterfowl were important additions to the diet.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Many of these food traditions are especially predominant in many parts of the rural South.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Traditionally prepared soul food is often high in fat, sodium, and starch.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Highly suited to the physically demanding lives of laborers, farmhands and rural lifestyles generally, it is now a contributing factor to obesity, heart disease, high cholesterol, high blood pressure, and diabetes in a population that has become increasingly more urban and sedentary.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] There is some resistance to such changes, however, as they involve deviating from long culinary tradition.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Other soul foods African Americans cook are chicken and waffles and desserts like banana pudding, peach cobbler, red velvet cake and sweet potato pie.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Kool-Aid is considered a soul food beverage.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Rice, common to Lowcountry region of South Carolina and Georgia, was imported from the island of Madagascar.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Soul food is similar to gypsy cooking in Europe.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] As with other American racial and ethnic groups, African Americans observe ethnic holidays alongside traditional American holidays.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Holidays observed in African-American culture are also widely considered to be American holidays.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The birthday of noted American civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr. has been observed nationally since 1983.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] It is one of four federal holidays named for an individual.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Black History Month is another example of another African-American observance that has been adopted nationally and its teaching is even required by law in some states.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Black History Month is an attempt to focus attention on previously neglected aspects of the American history, chiefly the lives and stories of African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] It is observed during the month of February to coincide with the founding of the NAACP and the birthdays of Frederick Douglass, a prominent African-American abolitionist, and Abraham Lincoln, the United States president who signed the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] On June 7, 1979, President Jimmy Carter decreed that June would be the month of black music.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Black Music Month is observed through various events urging citizens to revel in various genres of music, including gospel and hip-hop.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African-American musicians, singers, and composers are acknowledged for their contributions to the nation's history and culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Less-widely observed outside of the African-American community is Emancipation Day popularly known as Juneteenth or Freedom Day, in recognition of the official reading of the Emancipation Proclamation on June 19, 1865, in Texas.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Juneteenth is a day when African Americans reflect on their unique history and heritage.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] It is one of the fastest growing African-American holidays with observances in the United States.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Juneteenth was recognized as federal holiday in 2021, and was first observed as such on June 19, 2021.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] In addition, other holidays celebrated were African American Day in Louisiana along with African American Emancipation Day across the United States in the 19th century after the abolition of slavery.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Another holiday not widely observed outside of the African-American community is the birthday of Malcolm X.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The day is observed on May 19 in American cities with a significant African-American population, including Washington, D.C.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Another noted African-American holiday is Kwanzaa.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Like Emancipation Day, it is not widely observed outside of the African-American community, although it is growing in popularity with both African-American and African communities.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African-American scholar and activist "Maulana" Ron Karenga invented the festival of Kwanzaa in 1966, as an alternative to the increasing commercialization of Christmas.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Derived from the harvest rituals of Africans, Kwanzaa is observed each year from December 26 through January 1.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Although many African-American names are common among the larger population of the United States, distinct naming trends have emerged within African-American culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Prior to the 1950s and 1960s, most African-American names closely resembled those used within European American culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] A dramatic shift in naming traditions began to take shape in the 1960s and 1970s in America.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] With the rise of the mid-century Civil Rights Movement, there was a dramatic rise in names of various origins.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The practice of adopting neo-African or Islamic names gained popularity during that era.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Efforts to recover African heritage inspired selection of names with deeper cultural significance.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Before this, using African names was uncommon because African Americans were several generations removed from the last ancestor to have an African name, as slaves were often given the names of their enslavers, which were of European origin.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African-American names have origins in many languages including French, Latin, English, Arabic, and African languages.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] One very notable influence on African-American names is the Muslim religion.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Islamic names entered the popular culture with the rise of The Nation of Islam among Black Americans with its focus on civil rights.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The popular name "Aisha" has origins in the Qur'an.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Names of African origin began to crop up as well.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Names like Ashanti, Tanisha, Aaliyah, Malaika have origins in the continent of Africa.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] By the 1970s and 1980s, it had become common within the culture to invent new names, although many of the invented names took elements from popular existing names.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Prefixes such as La/Le-, Da/De-, Ra/Re-, or Ja/Je- and suffixes such as -ique/iqua, -isha, and -aun/-awn are common, as well as inventive spellings for common names.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Even with the rise of creative names, it is also still common for African Americans to use biblical, historic, or European names.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] When slavery was practiced in the United States, it was common for families to be separated through sale.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Even during slavery, however, many African-American families managed to maintain strong familial bonds.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Free African men and women, who managed to buy their own freedom by being hired out, who were emancipated, or who had escaped the slave holder, often worked long and hard to buy the members of their families who remained in bondage and send for them.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Others, separated from blood kin, formed close bonds based on fictive kin; *play* relations, *play* aunts, cousins, and the like.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] This practice, a holdover from African oral traditions such as *sanankouya*, survived Emancipation, with non-blood family friends commonly accorded the status and titles of blood relations.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] 76% of African Americans have said they have spoken with their relatives to learn about their family history.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] When African Americans were taken from their homes and forced into slavery, they were separated from mothers, fathers, sisters and brothers and were torn apart from extensive kinship networks.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Immediately after slavery, African-American families struggled to reunite and rebuild what had been taken.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] As late as 1960, when most African Americans lived under some form of segregation, 78 percent of African-American families were headed by married couples.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] This number steadily declined during the latter half of the 20th century.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] For the first time since slavery, a majority of African-American children live in a household with only one parent, typically the mother.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] This apparent weakness is balanced by mutual-aid systems established by extended family members to provide emotional and economic support.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Older family members pass on social and cultural traditions such as religion and manners to younger family members.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] In turn, the older family members are cared for by younger family members when they cannot care for themselves.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] These relationships exist at all economic levels in the African-American community, providing strength and support both to the African-American family and the community.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African Americans are less likely to own a pet.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Interracial marriages have increased for African Americans since Loving Vs.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] More than half (51.2%) of African-American children lived with a single parent in 2022, compared with about one in five (21.3%) of white American children.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Since the passing of the Voting Rights Act of 1965, African Americans are voting and being elected to public office in increasing numbers.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] As of 2008 the United States had approximately 10,000 African-American elected officials.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African Americans overwhelmingly associate with the Democratic Party.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Only 11% of African Americans supported George W.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] In 2016, only 8% of African Americans voted for Republican Donald Trump while 88% of African Americans voted for Democrat Hillary Clinton.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Social issues such as racial profiling, racial disparities in sentencing, higher rates of poverty, lower access to health care and institutional racism in general are important to the African-American community.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African-Americans may express political and social sentiments through hip-hop culture, including graffiti, break-dancing, rapping, and more.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] This cultural movement makes statements about historical, as well as present-day topics like street culture and incarceration, and oftentimes expresses a call for change.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Hip-hop artists play a prominent role in activism and in fighting social injustices, and have a cultural role in defining and reflecting on political and social issues.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Prominent leaders in the Black church have demonstrated against gay-rights issues such as gay marriage.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] This stands in stark contrast to the down-low phenomenon of covert male–male sexual acts.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Some within the African-American community take a different position, notably the late Coretta Scott King and the Reverend Al Sharpton.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Sharpton, when asked in 2003 whether he supported gay marriage, replied that he might as well have been asked if he supported black marriage or white marriage.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] One of the most well known social and political organizations of Black culture is the Black Panther Party, a now-defunct African-American socialist organization.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Black Culture also utilizes cultural slogans for social and political standing such as Say it Loud, I'm Black and I'm Proud, Black Card, and even "It's a Black Thing, You Wouldn't Understand", a popular slogan that was born inside of Black American culture, referring to their culture, not race.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The Black LGBT community refers to the African-American (Black) population who are members of the LGBT community, as a community of marginalized individuals who are further marginalized within their own community.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Surveys and research have shown that 80% of African Americans say gays and lesbians endure discrimination compared to the 61% of whites.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Black members of the community are seen as "other" due to their race and their sexuality, so they had to combat both racism and homophobia.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Black LGBT first started to be visible during the Harlem Renaissance when a subculture of LGBTQ African-American artists and entertainers emerged.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] This included people like Alain Locke, Countee Cullen, Langston Hughes, Claude McKay, Wallace Thurman, Richard Bruce Nugent, Bessie Smith, Ma Rainey, Moms Mabley, Mabel Hampton, Alberta Hunter, and Gladys Bentley.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Places like Savoy Ballroom and the Rockland Palace hosted drag-ball extravaganzas with prizes awarded for the best costumes.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Langston Hughes depicted the balls as "spectacles of color".
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Historian George Chauncey, author of *Gay New York: Gender, Urban Culture, and the Making of the Gay Male World, 1890–1940*, wrote that during this period "perhaps nowhere were more men willing to venture out in public in drag than in Harlem".
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African-American neighborhoods are types of ethnic enclaves found in many cities in the United States.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The formation of African-American neighborhoods is closely linked to the history of segregation in the United States, either through formal laws, or as a product of social norms.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Despite this, African-American neighborhoods have played an important role in the development of nearly all aspects of both African-American culture and broader American culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Due to segregated conditions and widespread poverty, some African-American neighborhoods in the United States have been called "ghettos".
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The use of this term is controversial and, depending on the context, potentially offensive.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Despite mainstream America's use of the term "ghetto" to signify a poor urban area populated by ethnic minorities, those living in the area often used it to signify something positive.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The African-American ghettos did not always contain dilapidated houses and deteriorating projects, nor were all of its residents poverty-stricken.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] For many African Americans, the ghetto was "home", a place representing authentic "blackness" and a feeling, passion, or emotion derived from the rising above the struggle and suffering of being of African descent in America.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] In African-American neighborhoods the churches may be important sources of social cohesion.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] For some African Americans, the kind spirituality learned through these churches works as a protective factor against the corrosive forces of racism.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Museums devoted to African-American history are also found in many African-American neighborhoods.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Many African-American neighborhoods are located in inner cities, and these are the mostly residential neighborhoods located closest to the central business district.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The built environment is often row houses or brownstones, mixed with older single-family homes that may be converted to multi-family homes.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] In some areas there are larger apartment buildings.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Shotgun houses are an important part of the built environment of some southern African-American neighborhoods.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The houses consist of three to five rooms in a row with no hallways.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] This African-American house design is found in both rural and urban southern areas, mainly in African-American communities and neighborhoods.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The Black American Heritage Flag is an ethnic flag that represents the culture and history of Black American ethnic groups.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The flag was created in 1967 by Melvin Charles and Gleason T.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] There are African-American social networking websites such as BlackPlanet.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Social media is an important political outlet for African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African-American teenagers are the biggest users of Instagram and Snapchat.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] TikTok, Facebook and YouTube are also popular among African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Historically, Black Americans have been excluded from various professions and have faced overrepresentation in certain fields.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The separation of the American labor force traces back to colonial times when white laborers frequently declined to associate with free blacks in the North.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Following the Civil War, as 4 million former slaves gained their freedom, white Southerners were intent on ensuring that African Americans remained engaged in low-level agricultural labor.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Vagrancy laws and limitations on labor mobility compelled numerous free blacks to become sharecroppers, a job that offered minimal prospects for social advancement.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] As the Southern United States started industrializing in the late 1800s and early 1900s, business owners barred Black Americans from skilled positions in Southern factories, while white unions in the North also discriminated against blacks.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Consequently, African Americans were increasingly restricted to unskilled jobs in lumber, mining, and shipping sectors—rural industries requiring inexpensive labor in isolated areas.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Labor camps had inadequate working conditions, and the pay was minimal.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] These circumstances compelled numerous African American women to join the labor force in the late 1800s to supply their families with essential income, a trend distinctive to the black community.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] In 1870, for instance, roughly 49 percent of black women in the country were employed, whereas only 16.5 percent of white women had jobs.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The vast majority of African American women employed were found in service positions such as laundresses, domestic workers, and cooks.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] While certain black men and women attempted to push for improved working conditions, social obstacles in the South rendered their efforts mostly ineffective.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] By 1900, almost 85 percent of African Americans in the South were employed as laborers, farmers, planters, farm supervisors, domestic workers, waitstaff, and laundry employees.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African Americans have used various herbs such as black walnut, elderberry, sage, mullein, cotton, sassafras, basil leaf and wormwood.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Slave women used cotton seeds, bark and roots for menstrual issues and to prevent pregnancies.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Wiggers are white people who appropriate black culture.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] White people such as Eminem have utilized, used, adopted, and appropriated elements of African American culture as a means to articulate their own dissent.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] In 2015, Rachel Dolezal went viral for pretending to be black.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Other white celebrities who have been accused of appropriating African-American culture are Ariana Grande, Kim Kardashian, Iggy Azalea, Post Malone and Elvis Presley.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African Americans have valued education since slavery.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African-American communities have worked together to firm and finance public schools.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Even when they were barred from accessing education, Black Americans worked together with their supporters to build black colleges for black people.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Education for black slaves was heavily prohibited.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Enslaved black children and black adults had to take extreme measures to gain literacy, including having to attend underground schools.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] White Southern slaveholders generally opposed slave literacy in the Southern United States.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Some of the most prominent institutions of Black Culture are the historically Black Colleges and Universities, known as HBCUs.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] There are over 100 HBCUs in the United States of America.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African-American literature emerged in the 18th century, with Phillis Wheatley, an enslaved author, being the first African American to have written published books of poetry.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Washington, Richard Wright, Gwendolyn Brooks, and Alice Walker.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Before the American Civil War, the literature primarily consisted of memoirs by people who had escaped from enslavement the genre of slave narratives included accounts of life in enslavement and the path of justice and redemption to freedom.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] There was an early distinction between the literature of freed slaves and the literature of free blacks born in the North.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Free blacks expressed their oppression in a different narrative form.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Free blacks in the North often spoke out against enslavement and racial injustices by using the spiritual narrative.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] The spiritual addressed many of the same themes of enslaved people narratives but has been largely ignored in current scholarly conversation.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Historically, African-American folklore revolved around the storytelling and oral history of enslaved African Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Prevalent themes in African-American folktales include tricksters, life lessons, the hardships of slavery, and heartwarming tales.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] African Americans told stories of folk spirits that could outwit their slaveholders and defeat their enemies.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] These folk stories gave hope to enslaved people that folk spirits would free them from slavery.
[src:african-american-culture/african-american-culture-p02] Folktales have been used to perpetuate negative stereotypes about the African-American community.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The **African Methodist Episcopal Church**, usually called the **AME Church** or **AME**, is a Methodist denomination based in the United States.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] It adheres to Wesleyan–Arminian theology and has a connexional polity.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] It cooperates with other Methodist bodies through the World Methodist Council and Wesleyan Holiness Connection.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Though historically a black church and the first independent Protestant denomination to be founded by Black people, the African Methodist Episcopal Church welcomes and has members of all ethnicities.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The AME Church was founded by Richard Allen (1760–1831) in 1787 when he called together five African American congregations of the previously established Methodist Episcopal Church with the hope of escaping the discrimination that was commonplace in society, including some churches.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] It was among the first denominations in the United States to be founded for this reason (rather than for theological distinctions).
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The denomination then expanded west and through the South, particularly after the American Civil War (1861–1865).
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The AME Church currently has 20 districts, each with its own bishop: 13 are based in the United States, mostly in the South, while seven are based in Africa.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The global membership of the AME is around 2.5 million members, and it remains one of the largest Methodist denominations in the world.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] taken to the Americas) as a response to being officially discriminated against by white congregants in the Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The church was not founded in Africa, nor is it exclusively for people of African descent.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] It is open and welcoming to people of all ethnic groups, origins, nationalities, and colors, although its congregations are predominantly made up of black Americans.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] George's Methodist Church left the congregation when faced with racial discrimination, but continued with the Methodist doctrine and the order of worship.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The denomination leaders are bishops of the church.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The AME Church worked out of the Free African Society (FAS), which Richard Allen, Absalom Jones, and other free blacks established in Philadelphia in 1787.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] George's Methodist Episcopal Church because of discrimination.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] These members erected a site of worship to escape the "unkind treatment of their white brethren, who considered them a nuisance in the house of worship." They were told if they did not give up this space, they would be publicly expelled from the church.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] They resigned, an action that was supported by some white benefactors, including one who ordained Absalom Jones as their pastor.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Although Allen and Jones were both accepted as preachers, they were limited to black congregations.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] In addition, the blacks were made to sit in a separate gallery built in the church when their portion of the congregation increased.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] George's made plans to transform their mutual aid society into an African congregation.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Although the group was originally non-denominational, eventually members wanted to affiliate with existing denominations.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Allen led a small group who resolved to remain Methodist.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] They formed the Bethel African Methodist Episcopal Church in 1793.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] In general, they adopted the doctrines and form of government of the Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] In 1794 Bethel AME was dedicated with Allen as pastor.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] To establish Bethel's independence, Allen successfully sued in the Pennsylvania courts in 1807 and 1815 for the right of his congregation to exist as an institution independent of white Methodist congregations.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Because black Methodists in other middle Atlantic communities also encountered racism and desired religious autonomy, Allen called them to meet in Philadelphia in 1816 to form a new Wesleyan denomination.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Sixteen representatives, from Bethel African Church in Philadelphia and African churches in Baltimore, MD, Wilmington, DE, Attleboro, PA, and Salem, NJ, met to form a church organization or connection under the title of the "African Methodist Episcopal Church".
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] It began with eight clergy and five churches, and by 1846 had grown to 176 clergy, 296 churches, and 17,375 members.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Safe villages, like the village of Lima, Pennsylvania, were set up with nearby AME churches and were sometimes involved in the Underground Railroad.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The 20,000 members in 1856 were located primarily in the North.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] AME national membership (including probationers and preachers) jumped from 70,000 in 1866 to 207,000 in 1876.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The church also expanded internationally during this period.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Other Bermudians, such as First Sergeant Robert John Simmons of the 54th Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry Regiment, fought to end slavery in the United States.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Among the numerous residents of the American South with ties to Bermuda was Denmark Vesey, who was brought to South Carolina from Bermuda as a slave before purchasing his freedom.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Vesey was a founder of Mother Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church before his execution after conviction in a show trial resulting from white hysteria over an alleged conspiracy for a slave revolt in 1822.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The majority of the population of Bermuda during the first century of settlement was European, with free and enslaved blacks primarily from the Spanish West Indies and Native Americans, primarily from New England (anyone not entirely of European ancestry was counted as *coloured*).
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] As any child of a coloured and a white parent was counted as coloured, the ratio of the white to coloured population shifted during the course of the 18th century (4,850 whites and 3,514 coloured in 1721; but 4,755 whites and 5,425 coloured in 1811).
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The Church of England was the established church, and was the only church originally permitted to operate in Bermuda.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Presbyterians were permitted to have a separate church and to conduct their own services during the 18th century.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The Wesleyan Methodists sought to include enslaved blacks and a law was passed by the Parliament of Bermuda in 1800 barring any but Church of England and Presbyterian ministers from preaching.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The Methodist Reverend John Stephenson was incarcerated in December, 1800, for six months for preaching to slaves.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The law and attitudes changed during the course of the following century, but any church organised by blacks and organising blacks would not be welcomed by the white dominated Government.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Stephenson was followed in 1808 by the Reverend Joshua Marsden.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] There were 136 members of the Society when Marsden left Bermuda in 1812.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Lloyd's negative comments on the *dissenters* was in reference to the Wesleyan Methodists.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The degree of education of coloured Bermudians would be noted by later visitors, also.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The foundation stone of a Wesleyan Methodist Chapel was laid in St.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] George's Town on the 8 June 1840, the local Society (by then numbering 37 class leaders, 489 members, and 20 other communicants) having previously occupied a small, increasingly decrepit building that had been damaged beyond use in a storm in 1839.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The AME First District website records that in the autumn of 1869, *three farsighted Christian men—Benjamin Burchall of St.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Jennings of Devonshire and Charles Roach Ratteray of Somerset—set in motion the wheels that brought African Methodism to* Bermuda.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] As the Imperial Government had ruled that the AME Church could operate in the United Kingdom, the first AME church in Bermuda was erected in 1885 in Hamilton Parish, on the shore of Harrington Sound, and titled St.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] John African Methodist Episcopal Church (the congregation had begun previously as part of the British Methodist Episcopal Church of Canada).
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Although the Church of England (since 1978, titled the Anglican Church of Bermuda) remains the largest denomination in Bermuda (15.8%), the AME quickly flourished (accounting for 8.6% of the population today), overtaking the Wesleyan Methodists (2.7% today).
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The rise of the Wesleyan-Holiness movement in Methodism influenced the African Methodist Episcopal Church, with Jarena Lee and Amanda Smith preaching the doctrine of entire sanctification throughout pulpits of the connexion.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] In the 19th century, the AME Church of Ohio collaborated with the Methodist Episcopal Church, a predominantly white denomination, in sponsoring the second independent historically black college (HBCU), Wilberforce University in Ohio.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] By 1880, AME operated over 2,000 schools, chiefly in the South, with 155,000 students.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] For school houses they used church buildings; the ministers and their wives were the teachers; the congregations raised the money to keep schools operating at a time the segregated public schools were starved of funds.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] After the America Civil War, Bishop Henry McNeal Turner (1834–1915) was a major leader of the AME and played a role in Republican Party politics.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] In 1863 during the American Civil War, Turner was appointed as the first black chaplain in the United States Colored Troops.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Afterward, he was appointed to the Freedmen's Bureau in Georgia.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] He settled in Macon, Georgia, and was elected to the state legislature in 1868 during Reconstruction.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] He planted many AME churches in Georgia after the war.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] In 1880 he was elected as the first southern bishop of the AME Church after a fierce battle within the denomination.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Angered by the Democrats' regaining power and instituting Jim Crow laws in the late nineteenth century South, Turner was the leader of black nationalism and proposed emigration of blacks to Africa.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The African Methodist Episcopal Church has a unique history as it is the first major religious denomination in the western world that developed because of race rather than theological differences.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] It was the first African-American denomination organized and incorporated in the United States.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The church was born in protest against racial discrimination and slavery.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Among Wilberforce University's early founders was Salmon P.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Chase, then-governor of Ohio and the future Secretary of Treasury under President Abraham Lincoln.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Other members of the FAS wanted to affiliate with the Episcopal Church and followed Absalom Jones in doing that.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] In 1792, they founded the African Episcopal Church of St.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Thomas, the first Episcopal church in the United States with a founding black congregation.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] In 1804, Jones was ordained as the first black priest in the Episcopal Church.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] While the AME is doctrinally Methodist, clergy, scholars, and lay persons have written works that demonstrate the distinctive racial theology and *praxis* that have come to define this Wesleyan body.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] DuBois said AME was "the greatest Negro organization in the world".
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] In an address to the 1893 World's Parliament of Religions, Bishop Benjamin W.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Arnett reminded the audience of blacks' influence in the formation of Christianity.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Tanner wrote in 1895 in *The Color of Solomon – What?* that biblical scholars wrongly portrayed the son of David as a white man.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] In the post-civil rights era, theologians James Cone, Cecil W.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Cone, and Jacqueline Grant, who came from the AME tradition, criticized Euro-centric Christianity and African-American churches for their shortcomings in resolving the plight of those oppressed by racism, sexism, and economic disadvantage.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The World Council of Churches estimates the membership of the AME Church at around 2,510,000; 3,817 pastors, 21 bishops and 7,000 congregations.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The General Conference is the supreme body of the African Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] It is composed of the bishops, as *ex officio* presidents, according to the rank of election, and an equal number of ministerial and lay delegates, elected by each of the annual conferences and the lay electoral colleges of the annual conferences.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Other *ex officio* members are: the general officers, college presidents, deans of theological seminaries; and chaplains in the regular United States Armed Forces.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The General Conference meets every four years, but may have extra sessions in certain emergencies.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] At the General Conference of the AME Church, notable and renowned speakers have been invited to address the clergy and laity of the congregation.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Such as in 2008, the church invited then Senator Barack H.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] Obama, and in 2012, the church invited then First Lady of the United States Michelle Obama.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The Council of Bishops is the executive branch of the church.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] It has the general oversight of the church during the interim between general conferences.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The AME Council of Bishops shall meet annually at such time and place as the majority of the council shall determine and also at such other times as may be deemed necessary in the discharging its responsibility as the executive branch of the African Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] This council shall hold at least two public sessions at each annual meeting.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] At the first, complaints and petitions against a bishop shall be heard, at the second, the decisions of the council shall be made public.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The Board of Incorporators, also known as the General Board of Trustees, has the supervision, in trust, of all connectional property of the church and is vested with authority to act in behalf of the AME Church wherever necessary.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The Judicial Council is the highest judicatory body of the African Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] It is an appellate court, elected by the General Conference and is amenable to it.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The African Methodist Episcopal Church cooperates with other Methodist bodies through the World Methodist Council and Wesleyan Holiness Connection.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The AME motto, "God Our Father, Christ Our Redeemer, Holy Spirit Our Comforter, Humankind Our Family", reflects the basic beliefs of the African Methodist Episcopal Church.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The basic foundations of the beliefs of the church can be summarized in the Apostles' Creed, and the 25 Articles of Religion, held in common with other Methodist denominations.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The church also observes the official bylaws of the AME Church.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The "Doctrine and Discipline of the African Methodist Episcopal Church" is revised at every AME General Conference and published every four years.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The AME Church also follows the rule that a minister of the denomination must retire at age 75, with bishops, more specifically, being required to retire upon the general conference nearest their 75th birthday.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The AME Church is active regarding issues of social justice and has invested time in reforming the criminal justice system.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The AME Church also opposes "elective abortion".
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] On women's issues, the AME has supported gender equality and, in 2000, first elected a woman to become bishop.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] While always being open to people of all racial backgrounds, the AME has advocated for the civil and human rights of ethnic minorities, such as African Americans, through social improvement, religious autonomy, and political engagement.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The African Methodist Episcopal Church unanimously voted to forbid ministers from blessing same-sex unions in July 2004.
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The church leaders stated that homosexual activity "clearly contradicts [their] understanding of Scripture" and that the call of the African Methodist Episcopal Church "is to hear the voice of God in our Scriptures".
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The AME Church voted to take "a stand against climate change".
[src:african-american-culture/ame-church] The African Methodist Episcopal Church has been one of the forerunners of education within the African-American community.
